player.seasonOutlook: Those hoping for a breakout season from Suzuki a year ago got their wish, as the No. 13 overall pick from 2017 set new career-best marks in goals (33), assists (44), points (77) and power-play points (31 in 82 games). While the production was excellent, it's worth noting Suzuki has never been a guy that shoots the puck much (185 shots on goal last season), so it may be difficult for him to take another step forward. That said, he's locked into a massive role as Montreal's No. 1 center and hasn't missed a game in his career. That's more than enough to make Suzuki worthy of a mid-round fantasy selection.

Playing in his age-35 season, his 18th in the NHL, Staal's offensive numbers again dipped considerably. He appeared in 80 games, posting a measly 10 goals and 30 points. Staal added one goal and one assist in 11 postseason appearances. Staal is always good for upwards of 150 hits and remains one of the best defensive centers in the league, but it's nearly impossible to find a silver lining these days from a fantasy standpoint. Signed for three more years and armed with a no-move clause in his contract, Staal is a lock to remain on Carolina's roster for a while, although he's a full fade on draft day.

The Stars had a great year as a team last season, but they had a handful of guys mildly disappoint from a fantasy perspective, Heiskanen included. He missed ten games in January with a lower-body issue and that impacted his totals. The Finn posted nine goals and 54 points (21 on the power play) in 71 games, a year removed from a 11-goal, 73-point (34 with man advantage) performance in 79 appearances. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming year at age 25, Heiskanen looks like a prime rebound candidate. His usage will be massive for a group which again projects as one of the best teams in the NHL, and that's exactly the type of player you want to target on draft day.

Signed to a one-year, $3 million contract by Dallas last summer after being bought out by Nashville, Duchene rewarded the Stars with 25 goals and 65 points in 80 games. He added 16 power-play points, his second-highest mark in the past decade. Duchene, now 33 years old, certainly could have found a more lucrative deal on the open market but elected to return to Dallas for the same one-year, $3 million commitment he signed a year earlier. The ideal middle-six center at this stage of his career, Duchene should push for similar numbers in 2024-25, giving him late-round fantasy value in most formats.

Another year, another 50-plus point campaign for Huberdeau, as he registered 12 goals and 40 helpers in 81 regular-season outings for the Flames. While he may not be the same player who compiled 115 points back in 2021-22 while playing for the Panthers, the 31-year-old Quebec native still managed to put together his seventh consecutive 50-point season. With the man advantage, Huberdeau continued to offer decent productivity thanks to 19 power-play points. A lock for a first-line role, Huberdeau could link up free-agent signing Anthony Mantha on the top line, along with Nazem Kadri, which could help bolster Huberdeau's overall numbers at even strength.

Getting a boatload of ice time on the going-nowhere Sharks, Zetterlund was an extremely pleasant surprise last season. He tallied 24 goals and 44 points (16 with the man advantage) in 82 games, chipping in 120 hits for good measure. Of course, that offensive production came with a minus-34 rating. A repeat performance seems unlikely. A good chunk of Zetterlund's massive workload seems likely to go to 2024 No. 1 overall pick Macklin Celebrini, along with 2023 No. 4 overall pick Will Smith, both of whom are set to join the San Jose lineup full-time in 2024-25. The upside simply isn't there to make Zetterlund an option in anything but the very deepest of leagues.

After reaching personal bests in 2022-23 with 37 assists and 56 points, Backlund dropped to 15 goals and 39 points last campaign. He has finished with 39 points in two of the past three seasons while surpassing the 200-shot plateau each time. Backlund logged a career-high 19:14 of average ice time per contest in 2023-24 while playing in all situations. His reliability and durability make him a useful player for the Flames. Backlund could reach the 40-point mark in the 2024-25 season, but his fantasy value will likely be limited to a waiver-wire option for periods when he goes through a hot streak offensively.

Like every other member of the Sabres offense, Cozens burned every manager that reached for him in fantasy drafts a season ago. He managed just 18 goals and 47 points in 79 games, a far cry from the 31 goals and 68 points he produced in 81 games in his 2022-23 breakout campaign. Cozens' shooting percentage dipped from 14.7 percent to 9.0 percent, while his role with the power-play decreased, leading to just 10 points with the man advantage. Still just 23 years of age, Cozens would appear to be a strong bounce-back candidate for a team that made no notable offensive additions in free agency, but not much has gone right in Buffalo over the better part of the past two decades.

A model of consistency, Lindell has finished with somewhere between 24-26 points each of the past three seasons. He posted a plus-17 rating a year ago, the eighth straight year he was a plus player, while Lindell also averaged 20-plus minutes per game (20:28) for the seventh time in the past eight years. Lindell saw some power-play time early in his career, but that has dried up completely with the likes of Miro Heiskanen and Thomas Harley on the Dallas roster. Lindell is typically good for roughly 150 blocked shots per season, but there simply isn't enough production in any other category to make him a viable fantasy asset.

Limited to just 46 games two years ago due to a shoulder injury, Caufield returned last season and appeared fully healthy. He played in all 82 games for Montreal, posting career-best marks in goals (28), assists (37), points (65), average time on ice (19:25) and power-play points (21). Caufield's 314 shots on goal placed him seventh in the NHL. The crazy thing is that Caufield's 8.9 percent shooting percentage was by far the lowest of his career, suggesting some positive regression is due this coming campaign. Locked into top line and first power-play unit roles for the Canadiens, Caufield is a solid early-round fantasy option, with additional value in formats which place an extra emphasis on goals scored.

To the surprise of absolutely no one, it turned out one dreadful rookie season at age 18 wasn't enough to write Slafkovsky off completely. The No. 1 overall pick from 2022 rebounded in a major way in his second NHL campaign, posting 20 goals, 50 points, 152 shots on goal, 14 power-play points and 152 hits in 82 games. Included in there was a stretch late in the year in which Slafkovsky had points in 12 of 13 games. The consistency was great to see and bodes well for Slafkovsky taking another step forward in 2024-25. This may be the final season in which you can get him at any sort of discount in your fantasy draft.

Eklund finally grabbed a full-time role for the forever-rebuilding Sharks a season ago and had a nice year. He appeared in 80 games, finishing with 16 goals and 45 points, including 16 with the man advantage. That's the good news. The bad news is that Eklund finished with a minus-45 rating, worst in the entire NHL. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 22, Eklund remains one of San Jose's most important long-term pieces. Just keep in mind another horrific plus-minus rating will almost certainly be forthcoming in 2024-25.

Taking on a massive role for the tanking Sharks, Granlund came out of seemingly nowhere to produce 12 goals and 60 points in 69 games in first season in San Jose. His 23 power-play points were the second-most of his 12-year NHL career. It was a great story, but the odds of a repeat performance seem extremely slim. The Sharks will be adding all-world prospects Macklin Celebrini and Will Smith to the lineup, plus they signed Tyler Toffoli in free agency. That appears to all add up to far less usage for Granlund, making him a fantasy option in only deeper formats for the 2024-25 campaign.

Dahlin had a strange season. He tallied a career-high 20 goals, but his assist numbers were way down and as a result he finished with just 59 points in 81 games compared to the 73 points in 78 games he posted a year prior. He also saw 34 seconds less of power-play time per game, which helps explains why he managed 12 fewer points (20) a man up than the previous season. On a more positive note, Dahlin set new career-best marks in shots on goal (235), hits (195) and blocked shots (154). If you play in a format which values those statistics, Dahlin is a no-doubt No. 1 fantasy defender. If your league values just scoring numbers, he's best suited as a high-end No. 2 guy.

Toews may not put up the gaudy point totals of teammate Cale Makar or some of the other top rearguards in the league, but he's unquestionably been one of the best defenders in the NHL for many years now. Toews appeared in all 82 regular-season games for Colorado a year ago, posting 12 goals and exactly 50 points for a second straight year. He was also a plus-28, which was somehow his worst mark in the past four years. There's a ceiling to Toews' offensive production simply because Makar is around, but if the latter suffered an injury, the sky would be the limit. As is, Toews remains one of the safest picks among fantasy defensemen.

Playing nearly the entirety of last season at age 20, Johnston took another step towards stardom for Dallas. He set career-highs in goals (32), assists (33), points (65), shots on goal (216), average time on ice (17:00), and power-play points (10 in 82 games). Johnston added 10 goals and 16 points in 19 playoff appearances. If you're looking for one young player in the NHL who appears ready to explode, this is your guy. Johnston should be elevated to the No. 1 power-play unit for the Stars following the retirement of veteran Joe Pavelski, making him a legitimate point-per-game candidate in 2024-25.

Those that spent a late first-rounder on Rantanen in fantasy leagues last year were rewarded for their efforts, as the talented Finn posted 42 goals and 104 points in 80 games for the Avalanche. His 40 power-play points were a new career-best mark, while Rantanen also added 250-plus shots on goal (271) for a third consecutive year. Playing alongside one of the best players in the world in Nathan MacKinnon and eligible for unrestricted free agency in the summer of 2025, Rantanen could be primed to take his production to an even higher level in a contract year. Invest with confidence on draft day.

Andersson's power-play time was way down last season and his offensive numbers predictably suffered as a result. He managed just eight points with the man advantage after posting no fewer than 19 power-play points the prior two years. Overall, Andersson had nine goals and 39 points in 78 games. Solid statistics, but nothing exceptional. The rest of Andersson's numbers looked just like normal. He had 159 shots on goal, a career-high 186 blocked shots, and averaged 23:50 of ice time per game, right in line with previous seasons. The Swede's fantasy value will come down to whether he can regain his role as the quarterback on Calgary's No. 1 PP unit. It's a situation to monitor in training camp.

Matheson was handed the role of quarterback on Montreal's No. 1 power-play unit a season ago and he ran with the opportunity. He finished with 11 goals and a career-best 62 points, including 28 with the man advantage, in 82 games. This was a guy that had 25 power-play points in 465 career games entering the year. The lone negative of Matheson's season was his horrific minus-24 rating. Matheson should again open the upcoming season in a similar role give how well he filled it last year, but it's worth noting that with top prospect Lane Hutson expected to make the Montreal roster, Matheson could see his power-play time decrease, potentially torpedoing his fantasy value in the process.

The Flames were a train wreck a year ago, but that didn't stop Weegar from having by far the best offensive season of his career. He finished with 20 goals, one of four NHL rearguards to reach that mark. Keep in mind this is a player than never had more than eight goals in any one season. Weegar posted 52 points in 82 games, including 15 with the man advantage. He had 10 power-play points in 387 career games entering the season. Toss in 194 hits and 200 blocked shots and you have elite all-around production. Whether or not Weegar will be able to come close to matching those numbers in 2024-25 remains to be seen, but he's a lock to receive a ton of playing time for Calgary, giving him a reasonable chance of doing so.

Eichel's surgically repaired neck held up just fine last season, but a knee injury cost him the better part of two months late in the year. He was his usual productive self when healthy, averaging more than a point per game (31 goals, 68 points in 63 games). Eichel added 22 points with the man advantage and fired 278 shots on goal, his most since the 2018-19 season with Buffalo. Eichel is a greater injury risk than many of the other top offensive players in the NHL, but he's also a lock to provide early round offensive numbers whenever he's in the lineup.

Konecny was the best player a year ago for a Philadelphia team which greatly exceeded expectations. His 33 goals, 68 points, and 244 shots on goal in 76 games were all career-best marks and Konecny's numbers would have looked even better had he not missed six games in late February with an upper-body ailment. Konecny's nine power-play points were his lowest mark in the past five years, but his 2:59 per game with the man advantage was the highest mark of his career, so he is due some positive regression in that area. The 27-year-old should once again be a useful late-round fantasy pick for those looking to add some offensive punch to their lineup this coming season.

Fresh off a 36-goal, 79-point 2022-23 campaign, Tuch burned fantasy managers in a major way last season. He appeared in 75 games, managing just 22 goals and 59 points. The main reason why was his lack of production with the man advantage. Tuch managed just 11 power-play points and averaged 2:38 of ice time a man up per game, down from the 20 power-play points and 3:21 per game he averaged a year prior. The Sabres made no notable additions to their forward group this offseason, meaning Tuch should be in a prime position to rebound this coming year.

Now 32 years old, the days of Seguin potting 40 goals in a single season and averaging upwards of a point-per-game have come and gone. That said, he scored 25 times last year, his most since the 2018-19 campaign, while cracking the 50-point barrier (52) for the second straight season. Seguin appears to have some gas left in the tank, but he plays for one of the best teams in the NHL. The Stars have a ton of offensive weapons at their disposal, meaning Seguin simply isn't going to see the usage needed to make for a significant fantasy asset. He's an option for managers in deeper formats looking for point production in the final rounds of their draft.

Thompson came nowhere near repeating his 47-goal, 94-point breakout 2022-23 performance. He missed nine games early in the year due to injury and never seemed to get back on track. He finished with 29 goals and 56 points in 71 games, seriously underwhelming numbers for a guy that was drafted as a late first-rounder in some formats a year ago. Thompson's greatest struggles came with the man advantage. He had only 16 power-play points compared to a whopping 34 two years ago. As is typically the case, the truth likely lies somewhere in the middle. Thompson should be better than last year and could easily threaten the point-per-game mark this coming year, but make sure you don't overpay for past production on draft day.

Josi will be entering his age-34 season, but his status as one of the top offensive rearguards in the game isn't in doubt. He played all 82 games for Nashville a year ago, leading all NHL defensemen in goals (23) and shots (268), while posting 85 points, including 33 with the man advantage. Josi added 151 blocked shots for good measure, his most since the 2015-16 campaign. It's exceedingly rare to find this type of all-around production from a defender, making Josi an anchor and no-doubt No. 1 fantasy rearguard heading into the upcoming season.

Peterka took a massive step forward in his second NHL season, finishing with 28 goals and 50 points in 82 games. He posted 226 shots on goal, over 100 more than in his rookie campaign. The production was remarkable considering Peterka had just three goals and seven points with the man advantage. Peterka won't turn 23 until next January, so there's clearly room for further improvement, but it will almost certainly take an increased power-play role for it to materialize. It's far from a guarantee, but the upside is there, especially after the Sabres jettisoned Jeff Skinner via a buyout.

Appearing in all 82 games for a third straight season, Benn was once again a productive player for Dallas, albeit not on the same level as the previous year. He closed with 21 goals and 60 points, including 22 with the man advantage. Benn's average ice time has been trending downwards for four straight years and the 15:07 per game he averaged last season was his lowest mark since the 2009-10 campaign when he was a 20-year-old rookie. With the Stars seemingly committed to getting more ice time to youngsters like Wyatt Johnston and Logan Stankoven, Benn could be looking at a further reduction in playing time, which would make him a fringe asset in standard fantasy formats.

During the offseason, Necas signed his second bridge deal, inking a two-year, $13 million contract with Carolina. The 24-year-old forward is coming off a second straight campaign in which he put up 20-plus goals while also reaching the 40-point threshold for the fourth consecutive year. Last season did see a drop in productivity for Necas with the man advantage, recording half as many power-play points (13) as he had in the prior season. Still, Necas should be an option for the top unit and a top-six assignment in 2024-25, offering plenty of top-end fantasy upside thanks to his offensive talent.

Burns' overall production was down last season, as he managed just 10 goals and 43 points in 82 games, but he did post 20 points with the man advantage, so fantasy managers got what they paid for. The biggest concern at this point, besides Burns' age (39), is the fact Carolina brought Shayne Gostisbehere back in unrestricted free agency, presumably with the intention of giving him a ton of PP time. Burns is the definition of durable, having not missed a game in 10 seasons, but when you combine his age with the fact he's shooting the puck less than ever, there are major concerns from a fantasy standpoint heading into 2024-25.

You know what you get from McNabb from a fantasy perspective. He had a career-high 26 points last season, but that's not why he's in your lineup. He's there for hits and blocked shots. McNabb's 207 blocks last season were a new high-water mark. That's the good news. The bad news is that his 148 hits were his lowest mark in seven years,  not counting the COVID-shortened 2020-21 campaign. Set to turn 34 this coming January, Vegas could look to limit the ice time of the aging McNabb, making him an increasingly risky fantasy option.

MacKinnon is fresh off what was by far his best season to date, which is saying something considering he's been one of the best players in the league for years. He netted 50-plus goals for the first time (51) while his 140 points in 82 games placed him second in the NHL in scoring behind only Tampa Bay's Nikita Kucherov. He led the NHL in shots on goal with 405 and set a new career high in power-play points with 48. This type of elite all-around fantasy production is nearly impossible to find on draft day. MacKinnon is deserving of a top-five overall fantasy pick in all formats this coming season.

Limited to just 50 games due to injury in 2022-23, Forsberg was back to full strength last season and the rest of the NHL paid for it. The Swede set new career-best marks in goals (48), assists (46), points (94), power-play points (32), hits (141) and shots on goal (347). The shot totals are the big one worth monitoring. Forsberg had never fired more than 247 pucks at net in any one season and he eclipsed that number by 100. It's the same exact thing Artemi Panarin did for the Rangers with similar results. Forsberg was available at a discount in fantasy drafts a year ago, but those days are over. Expect him to see him off the board in Round 2 this time around.

Kopitar displayed no real signs of slowing down in his age-36 season, managing 26 goals and 70 points (23 with the man advantage) in 81 games, numbers nearly identical to what he posted a year prior. That said, a deeper dive reveals one major concern. Kopitar had just 133 shots on goal. He finished with a 19.5 shooting percentage, by far the highest mark of his 18-year career. Something will almost certainly have to change next season for Kopitar to produce at a similar rate. Given his age, you're probably better off letting someone else take the plunge on the future Hall of Famer on draft day.

Kuzmenko produced 22 goals and 46 points in 72 regular-season games between Vancouver and Calgary last season. After being acquired by the Flames, he notched 14 tallies and 11 assists in 29 outings to salvage a disappointing start to the year. Kuzmenko worked well alongside Calgary's leading scorer, Nazem Kadri, and ranked fifth on the team with 12 power-play points. The 28-year-old Kuzmenko could surpass the 60-point mark in the 2024-25 campaign while topping 160 shots.

Fresh off his historic 25-goal, 101-point 2022-23 season in San Jose, Karlsson debuted in Pittsburgh last season and came crashing back down to Earth. He managed 11 goals and 56 points in 82 games. The production was fine, but far from elite. One could argue that the most important footnote regarding Karlsson's season was that the injury-prone rearguard didn't miss a single game for a second straight year. That said, the 34-year-old Swede seems like a poor bet moving forward. Combining his past injury history with the Penguins' status as a mediocre club and you have a guy best suited as a No. 2 fantasy defender as opposed to the true anchor of a roster.

One of the bright spots in Philadelphia's surprising season, Tippett is fresh off a year in which he appeared in 78 games and posted career-best marks in goals (28), assists (25), points (53) and hits (147). A volume shooter, Tippett finished with a whopping 289 shots on goal, eleventh-most in the NHL. Tippett is a candidate for increased production if the Flyers can improve their power play. They had the worst percentage in the league a season ago and it resulted in Tippett posting just eight points with the man advantage. There's legitimate mid-round fantasy upside here if everything breaks correctly.

Taking on a full-time role for Dallas last season for the first time in his career, Harley came out of nowhere to post 15 goals and 47 points in 79 games. He finished tied for 22nd among defensemen scoring despite adding just nine points with the man advantage. Harley, set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 23, looks like a rock-solid top-four defender for the Stars, but as is, it would likely take an injury to top rearguard Miro Heiskanen for Harley to take another significant step forward from a fantasy perspective in 2024-25.

Sanheim's usage was way up in his seventh NHL campaign, and he had a career year as a result. Appearing in 81 games, Sanheim posted new high-water marks in goals (10), assists (34), points (44), shots on goal (146), average time on ice (23:48), hits (94) and blocked shots (149). The numbers look great on paper, but there's a real question as to how sustainable the production is. Sanheim managed just five points with the man advantage. It's rare for a defender to post 40-plus points annually unless they are a real asset on the power play. Sanheim has fantasy value because his usage is so great, but what we saw from him last season may be his ceiling from a fantasy standpoint.

Buoyed by a likely unsustainable 15.7 shooting percentage, by far his highest mark to date, Coleman finished with a career-best 30 goals last season for the Flames. He had never posted more than 22 goals in any of his first six NHL seasons. Coleman is always good for upwards of 200 shots on goal and 100 hits, but he rarely produces with the man advantage, making him an increasingly risky fantasy option on a year-by-year basis. Set to turn 33 in late November, nothing in Coleman's profile suggests a repeat performance is forthcoming.

Gostisbehere's lone season in Detroit proved to be a strong one. He closed with 10 goals and 56 points, including 29 on the power play, in 81 games. It was Gostisbehere's most productive season with the man advantage since the 2017-18 campaign with Philadelphia. Entering unrestricted free agency this past July, Gostisbehere inked a three-year deal with Carolina worth $9.6 million. The Florida native closed the 2022-23 season with the Hurricanes, posting 10 points in 23 games. With Brent Burns nearing the end of his career and struggling mightily in the playoffs, Gostisbehere should be considered the favorite to quarterback Carolina's No. 1 power-play unit in 2024-25.

Fantasy managers hoping for a breakout season from Byfield got their wish. Taking on an enhanced role, often playing on Los Angeles' top line and top power-play unit, Byfield racked up 20 goals and 55 points, including 14 with the man advantage, in 80 games. He added 161 shots on goal and finished with a plus-19 rating for good measure. The No. 2 overall selection in 2020, Byfield has always been an all-world talent. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 22, Byfield is the most valuable long-term asset on the Kings roster. This will likely be your last chance to get him at any sort of discount on draft day.

Manson took a surprising step forward offensively last season, potting a career-high eight goals and finishing with 25 points in 76 games, his most since the 2017-18 campaign. While the increased production was nice, it's hardly a lock to carry over to this coming season. Manson sees zero power-play time, meaning his point totals are highly likely to fluctuate on a year-to-year basis. He did have 211 hits and 109 blocked shots last season, so he has some late-round value in formats which value such numbers, but that's about it.

Armia again missed significant time last season, appearing in just 66 of Montreal's 82 regular season games. He did tally a career-high 17 goals, however. Armia's 25 points were his most since the 2019-20 campaign. Armia has displayed the ability to provide offense in short spurts, but he's best served in a third-line role for the Canadiens. It would take multiple injuries for Armia to amass any significant fantasy value during the 2024-25 season.

Hintz finished with 30 goals in 2023-24, the third straight year he has reached that mark, but his overall numbers (30 goals, 35 assists, 65 points, 182 shots on goal, 19 power-play points) were down across the board compared to two seasons ago (37 goals, 38 assists, 75 points, 184 shots on goal, 21 power-play points). Hintz is a tough guy to get a read on from a fantasy perspective because he always seems to finish with outrageously high shooting percentages. His average number in that category over the past five seasons is 17.4 percent and that makes his goal totals difficult to predict on a year-by-year basis. That said, you should be just fine if you draft Hintz as a No. 3 forward in all fantasy formats this coming year.

Those that drafted Robertson in late in the first round a season ago on the strength of his 46-goal, 109-point 2022-23 campaign got burned to some extent. He still played well (29 goals, 80 points in 82 games), but the numbers were nowhere near what we saw the year prior. Robertston's shooting percentage dropped from 14.7 percent to 12.6 percent and his power-play numbers dipped from 41 points with the man advantage to 28 points a season ago. It's safe to project Robertson as a point-per-game guy moving forward, particularly because he hasn't missed a single game the past two years, but don't expect him to reach the century mark again this coming season.

Kempe's goal total was way down last season (28) compared to two years ago (41), but his assist totals (47, compared to 26 in 2022-23) were way up, and as a result, he finished with a career-high 75 points in 77 games. Kempe's 27 points with the man advantage were a new high-water mark, while he topped 240 shots on goal (246) and 110 hits (112) for a third straight year. Kempe would appear to have a limited ceiling, as there's a real chance we've already seen the best he has to offer, but set to play this entire upcoming season at age 28, he makes for a rock-solid middle-round fantasy pick in all formats.

Common sense suggests Crosby will slow down at some point, but then again, maybe not. He finished last season with 94 points in 82 games, the 19th straight season in which he averaged at least a point per game. Crosby's 42 goals were his most since the 2016-17 campaign. Toss in 278 shots on goal and 23 power-play points and you have an elite all-around fantasy contributor. Pittsburgh's aging core is not something you want to bet on from a fantasy standpoint, but that doesn't apply to Crosby. The 37-year-old future first-ballot Hall of Famer isn't a fantasy league-winner at this stage of his career, but good luck finding a steadier option in all formats.

Kadri's second season in Calgary went far better than his first. He finished with 29 goals and 75 points in 82 games, much better than the 24 goals and 56 points he managed in 82 games the year prior. Kadri added 22 power-play points and a career-high 277 shots on goal. The Flames aren't an offense you want to invest in from a fantasy perspective, but Kadri is locked into a major role, meaning he should once again be good for mid-round value in 2024-25.

Picking a perfect time to enter unrestricted free agency, Skjei appeared in 80 games for Carolina last season, posting 13 goals and a career-high 47 points. He managed 12 points with the man advantage despite averaging less than a minute (0:59) of power-play time per game. Priced out of a return to the Hurricanes, Skjei inked a seven-year, $49 million contract with the Predators. It seems like a reasonable landing spot from a fantasy standpoint. Roman Josi is locked in as the quarterback of Nashville's No. 1 power-play unit, but Skjei is the clear favorite to run the second group, meaning 40 points would appear to be well within range once again.

Foerster was excellent in his first full NHL season. The No. 23 overall pick from 2020 closed his rookie campaign with 20 goals, 33 points, 167 shots on goal and 101 hits in 77 games. He added eight points with the man advantage for good measure. As the Flyers continue their rebuild, Foerster has emerged as a key long-term piece for the club. He has more value in keeper and dynasty formats than redraft leagues, but Foerster should make for a decent late-round option in most leagues this coming fall.

With their season having gone off the rails, the Devils dealt Toffoli to Winnipeg in early March. He appeared in 79 games between the two teams, posting 33 goals and 55 points. His assist totals were way down, but Toffoli still managed 18 points with the man advantage. Toffoli followed the money to San Jose this past summer as a free agent, inking a four-year, $24 million deal with the Sharks. He's a lock to receive a ton of ice time with his new team, meaning he should put up his usual mid-round fantasy numbers, but keep in mind a horrific plus-minus rating will likely be attached.

Lehkonen was a popular breakout pick in fantasy drafts last fall following his stellar (51 points in 64 games) 2022-23 campaign, but a neck injury completely derailed his year. He missed more than two months with the ailment and ended up appearing in just 45 games, posting 16 goals and 34 points. If that's not bad enough, Lehkonen underwent offseason shoulder surgery. He's expected to be ready right around the start of training camp. The Finn is once again a sneaky late-round dart throw, but the injury risk here is real.

Stuck amid a deep rebuild in San Jose, Hertl hit the hockey version of the Powerball and was dealt to Vegas in early March. He missed part of the year with a knee injury, appearing in six games for the Golden Knights late in the year prior to their playoff run. Postseason included, Hertl finished with three goals and five points in 13 games with his new club. Hertl should obviously score at a more efficient pace than that this coming season, but keep in mind he's now playing for a team with countless more offensive weapons than the Sharks. Penciling him in for 25 goals and 55-60 points seems like a fair projection for Hertl in his first full year in Sin City.

Marchessault had arguably his best season to date a year ago and picked a perfect time for it. He finished with a career-best 42 goals in 82 games. His 69 points were Marchessault's most since the 2017-18 campaign. He added 266 shots on goal, 107 hits and 17 power-play points for good measure. Marchessault parlayed his stellar season into a five-year, $27.5 million deal with Nashville in unrestricted free agency. The 33-year-old should see similar new usage with his new club, making Marchessault a solid mid-round fantasy option in all formats this coming season.

One of the most consistent players in the entire NHL, Aho is fresh off another brilliant season. He posted career-best marks in points (89 in 78 games), power-play points (32), and plus-minus (plus-34), while potting 36 goals for a second straight year. Aho's ten game-winning goals were also a new high-water mark. Aho has also remained relatively healthy, missing a grand total of 14 games over the past three years combined. The Finn isn't likely to offer league-winning production in fantasy formats this coming fall, but you'd be hard pressed to find a more reliable option on draft day.

Fiala's usage was up a season ago, but it didn't lead to a significant increase in production. His 18:02 average time on ice, including 3:09 per game with the man advantage, were both new high-water marks, but his 29 goals and 73 points were right in line with the numbers we have seen from him in recent years. To Fiala's credit, he took advantage of the extra power-play time to post a career-best 30 points a man up. The 28-year-old Swiss winger has settled into a valuable source of secondary scoring for both the Kings and fantasy managers alike, making Fiala a reasonable middle-round target in all formats this coming season.

Named a finalist for the Norris Trophy as the best defenseman in the NHL for a fourth straight season, Makar posted a career-high 90 points in 77 games in 2023-24, placing him second to Vancouver's Quinn Hughes in terms of scoring amongst rearguards. Makar almost certainly would have led the league had he not missed a handful of games due to injury. His 39 power-play points were a new high-water mark, as were his 148 blocked shots. Simply put, Makar is unquestionably the most dynamic defender in the game today. A worthy late first-rounder in all fantasy formats, Makar is the greatest singular difference-maker at the position.

Svechnikov was again bit by the injury bug last season, as he missed at least six games on three separate occasions. All told, he finished with 19 goals and 52 points in 59 appearances for Carolina. He added 11 points in 11 playoff games. Fantasy managers have been waiting for a breakout performance from Svechnikov for years now. He seems to be ready to make the leap from a skills standpoint, but nagging injuries have always gotten in the way. Svechnikov always remains involved physically, posting 140-plus hits for three consecutive seasons, but he's going to have to find a way to remain in the lineup more consistently if he hopes to take another step forward offensively in 2024-25.

A lacerated spleen cost Stone 26 games and nearly two months' worth of action last season. He was his typical productive self (16 goals, 53 points in 56 games) when in the lineup and as is always the case, he managed to gut it out come playoff time. Stone is an excellent player, but one of the greatest injury risks in the league. The 56 regular-season games he played last season was his most in the last three years. With Vegas again projected to be one of the better teams in the league and their eyes fully focused on the postseason, Stone would again appear to be at major risk of missing a good chunk of regular-season action. Keep all of this in mind before taking the plunge on draft day.

Those expecting a breakout campaign from Jarvis a year ago got their wish. The 22-year-old posted new career-best marks in goals (33), assists (34), points (67), plus-minus (plus-23), game-winning goals (9), power-play points (20) and hits (115). Jarvis' 18.8 shooting percentage was high, so he's due some regression in that area, but his extreme usage should more than make up for it. This is probably the final year to get Jarvis at any sort of a discount in fantasy drafts, especially if the restricted free agent's contract negotiations linger into training camp.

York played a ton of minutes for the rebuilding Flyers last season, playing in all 82 games and finishing with 10 goals and 30 points, including six with the man advantage. York is clearly Philadelphia's best option in terms of a power-play quarterback, but Travis Sanheim and Jamie Drysdale are both candidates to see increased time in that area, meaning York is no lock for a breakout campaign. York should again be good for 30-plus points and is also an asset in formats that reward blocked shots, giving him value in deeper formats, but that might be about it.

There is no greater injury risk in the NHL than Landeskog. Now 31 years old, the Swede hasn't played a game since June 2022 due to a serious knee issue that has required multiple surgeries. Landeskog stated in late May that he doesn't plan on retiring and is instead focusing on preparing for the upcoming season. While that's all well and good, the odds would appear to be against him at this point. Even if Landeskog can come back, it's virtually impossible to imagine he would be cleared to be in the lineup every single night. It's simply not worth the headache at this point from a fantasy perspective.

Doughty continues to play a massive role for the Kings in the latter stages of his career. The 34-year-old averaged 25:48 of ice time per game last season, third in the NHL. He posted 15 goals, his most since the 2009-10 campaign, while Doughty finished with 50-plus points (50) for a second straight season. Toss in a plus-15 rating, 109 hits and 142 blocked shots and you have a legitimate all-around fantasy contributor. Doughty should continue to slot in as a No. 2 fantasy rearguard in all formats until further notice.

To say Laine had a tough season would be a massive understatement. He missed a ton of time due to injury and then entered the NHL/NHLPA Player Assistance Program in late January. All told, Laine appeared in just 18 games for the Blue Jackets, managing six goals and nine points. It was reported this summer that both the player and team would attempt to facilitate a trade to find Laine a new home, which finally came to fruition with a move to Montreal. Laine's goal-scoring upside is tantalizing, especially considering he could see plenty of minutes with the No. 1 power-play unit while also slotting into a top-six role.

Couture's 2023-24 campaign was marred by injury. He missed the first three-plus months with a lower-body ailment, returned for six games, then suffered a groin injury which ended his season. All told, Couture didn't score a single goal and managed just a lone assist. Couture hoped to resume skating in July, so he seems likely to be ready for training camp if he doesn't suffer any setbacks. At 35 years of age and playing for arguably the worst team in the NHL, there's no real reason to be excited about Couture from a fantasy standpoint this coming season.

Hayes spent just one season in St. Louis and saw his numbers drop immensely. He managed just 13 goals and 29 points in 79 games, a year removed from an 18-goal, 54-point performance with the Flyers. The lack of production was directly related to Hayes' decreased role with the man advantage. He had just five power-play points and averaged just 1:30 per game a man up, his lowest mark since the 2017-18 campaign. Hayes was dealt to the Penguins in late June in what was a straight salary dump for the Blues. The 32-year-old Massachusetts native will probably be a bit better offensively in 2024-25, but there's nothing to suggest Hayes will offer fantasy value in any format.

There's a case to be made that Rust is fresh off his best season to date. Yes, he missed 20 of Pittsburgh's 82 regular-season games, but he was a true difference maker when in the lineup, finishing with 28 goals and 56 points. With Jake Guentzel having moved on and Evgeni Malkin looking like a shell of his former self, Rust appears to be the prime beneficiary. He should skate on the Penguins' top line alongside Sidney Crosby and also on their top power-play unit, making Rust a sleeper to target on draft day.

An ideal middle-six shutdown center, Danault again did a nice job of providing some secondary offense for Los Angeles. He finished with 45-plus points (47) for the fifth time in the past six years, while also chipping in nine points with the man advantage. The 31-year-old will continue to see plenty of playing time because of his defensive prowess, but Danault has topped 20-plus goals just once in his nine-year NHL career, so there's limited upside here from a fantasy perspective. All told, you can probably do better on draft day.

The most positive thing you can say about Malkin's 2023-24 season is that he played in all 82 regular-season games for a second consecutive year. He closed with 27 goals and 67 points, the worst numbers of his career in any season in which he's played at least 62 games. The real drop in production came with the man advantage. Malkin managed just 18 power-play points, or exactly half of what he picked up the year prior. Between the past injury history and the fact Malkin is set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 38, your best course of action is to likely let another team take the plunge on the future first-ballot Hall of Famer on draft day.

Never one to pass on the chance to acquire a talented, high-profile player, Vegas acquired Hanifin from Calgary in early March and then signed him to an eight-year, $58.8 million contract in April. All told, Hanifin appeared in 80 regular-season games between the two teams, posting 13 goals and 47 points. The Golden Knights have other options like Shea Theodore and Alex Pietrangelo, but Hanifin was quarterbacking the club's No. 1 power-play unit during most of his time with Vegas, something which would cause his fantasy value to explode over the course of a full season if it sticks. Even if he's relegated to the second unit, Hanifin should see significant usage in all situations, making him a rock-solid fantasy defender this fall.

Entering his first season in Carolina after signing a three-year, $13.5 million deal last summer, Bunting posted 13 goals and 36 points in 60 games with the Hurricanes before being moved to the Penguins at the trade deadline in the Jake Guentzel deal. He was much more effective with his new club, managing 19 points in 21 games with Pittsburgh. An aging Pens team is not a group you want to invest in from a fantasy standpoint, but Bunting will play this entire season at age 29 and is locked into a top-six role for the club. You could do worse with a mid-to-late round draft pick this coming season.

Guhle was a key cog for Montreal last season, averaging north of 20 minutes per game (20:51) for a second straight year, while finishing with a career-high six goals and 22 points. Guhle missed the final seven games of the regular season with a hand issue, but joined Canada for the World Championships, so it clearly isn't a long-term concern. Guhle has late-round fantasy value in formats which value hits and blocked shots -- he had 116 hits and 178 blocks a year ago -- but there isn't enough scoring production here to make him worthy of a selection in standard leagues.

The Flyers got career-best performances from several players last season and Farabee was one of them. The Syracuse native appeared in all 82 games for a second straight year and set new high-water marks in goals (22), assists (28), points (50) and shots on goal (182). Philadelphia is unlikely to be a playoff team next season, meaning it may be difficult for Farabee to take a significant step forward in terms of production, but he should see enough usage to be worthy of a late-round pick in standard formats.

In what would be Stamkos' final season in Tampa Bay, he racked up 40 goals in 79 games, the seventh time in his storied career he's reached that plateau. He also averaged more than a point-per-game (81 points) for a third straight year. Looking to open cap space to sign Jake Guentzel, the Lightning let Stamkos walk as a free agent. He quickly inked a four-year, $32 million deal with the Predators. His numbers may dip some with his new club, but Nashville isn't paying Stamkos $8 million annually to take on a limited role. He should once again be good for 35 goals and 75 points in 2024-25.

Limited to just 64 games last season, Pietrangelo managed just 33 points in 64 games, one of the worst marks of his storied career. He scored just four goals due to a career-worst 2.8 shooting percentage. While it's tempting to draft Pietrangelo in hopes he'll rebound in 2024-25, keep in mind he's almost certainly behind fellow defenders Noah Hanifin and Shea Theodore in terms of earning power-play time. Toss in recent injury history combined with the fact Pietrangelo will be 35 years old this coming January and you have a guy that is more floor than ceiling from a fantasy standpoint.

The fact Letang managed 10 goals and 51 points in 82 games last season is truly remarkable considering he had just five (that is not a misprint) power-play points. A guy that has made his career by dominating a man up, Letang was relegated to the second power-play unit following the arrival of Norris Trophy winner Erik Karlsson and his numbers reflected that. The good news is that Letang appears to have plenty of gas left in the tank at age 37. Of course, there's no real reason to expect a role change in 2024-25, making Letang more of a depth fantasy option than the difference maker he has been most of his career.

Kucherov has been one of the best players in the NHL for a long time, but few could have seen this type of offensive explosion coming in his age-30 season. The Russian led the NHL in scoring with 144 points in 81 games. He finished with 100 assists, becoming just the fifth player in league history to reach that mark. Kucherov added career highs with 53 power-play points and 306 shots on goal for good measure. Kucherov battled injuries earlier in his career but has missed just one regular-season game over the past two years. A dip in production seems likely to come at some point, but it's hard to believe it will be this coming year given how great Kucherov looked in 2023-24.

It's certainly a stretch to say a guy who finished with 41 goals and 106 points in 81 games burned fantasy managers a season ago, but Draisaitl's numbers certainly took a step back from his massive 2022-23 campaign (52 goals, 128 points). The real drop came with the man advantage. Draisaitl had 62 power-play points two seasons ago, an entirely unsustainable number. He managed 39 this past season, still an elite total, and right in line with his other NHL campaigns. There's no concern regarding Draisaitl moving forward, as at 28 years of age and attached to the hip of the best player in the league, the big German once again has a case to be a top-10 player off the board in fantasy drafts in 2024-25.

Matthews came awfully close to scoring 70 goals this past season,  which would have made him the first player to reach that mark since Teemu Selanne and Alexander Mogilny netted 76 tallies in 1992-93. The 26-year-old Matthews had to settle for 69 tallies and a career-high 107 points in 81 games. No other NHL player had more than 57 goals. The model of consistency with the man advantage, Matthews has posted somewhere between 28-29 power-play points each of the past three years. His 369 shots on goal placed him third in the NHL. Matthews dealt with concussion symptoms in the playoffs, and while that's always scary to hear, there's no reason to believe it's a long-term concern at this point. The best pure sniper in the NHL, Matthews is a no-doubt top-five fantasy pick in all formats this coming season.

McDavid's streak of three straight years leading the NHL in scoring came to an end last season, likely due to the fact he missed six games due to injury. He still finished with 132 points in 76 games, including a whopping 100 assists. His 44 power-play points were also third-best in the league. Simply put, McDavid is the best player in the NHL. In his last 294 regular season games over the course of four seasons, McDavid has 173 goals, 513 points and a plus-106 rating. They're video game numbers. There's more elite talent in the league than ever before, but they all trail McDavid, who is the no-doubt first-round fantasy pick in all formats once again this year.

There were concerns prior to last season that the retirement of Patrice Bergeron would result in a negative impact on Pastrnak's numbers. No such luck. Yes, his goal total dropped from 61 two seasons ago to 47 last year, but he still finished with 110 points, including a whopping 35 with the man advantage. Pasta placed fifth in the NHL in scoring and his 382 shots on goal trailed only Colorado's Nathan MacKinnon (405). Toss in the fact he's still just 28 years of age and plays for one of the better teams in the NHL and Pastrnak will remain a no-doubt late first-round fantasy option in all formats heading into the 2024-25 campaign.

Buoyed by a completely unsustainable 24.5 shooting percentage -- well above his previous career-best mark of 19.2 percent -- Reinhart scored 57 goals (and 94 points) in 82 games last season. The number placed him second in the NHL behind only Toronto's Auston Matthews. With no choice but to pay up following his career year and a Stanley Cup championship, Florida inked Reinhart to an eight-year, $69 million deal following the season. Reinhart is an excellent player on one of the NHL's best teams, but perhaps no player in the league is at greater risk of burning fantasy managers this coming fall. Don't overpay on draft day.

Fresh off back-to-back 40 goals seasons in which he tallied north of 100 points both years, Tkachuk's numbers were way down in 2023-24. He posted 26 goals and 88 points in 80 games, but both Tkachuk and the Panthers could obviously care less about the dip in production given that they won the Stanley Cup. Under the hood, everything appears to be fine. Tkachuk tallied 32 power-play points and his dip in goals scored appears directly related to his unusually low 9.3 shooting percentage, his worst mark in seven years. Tkachuk is worth pouncing on if he is available at any sort of discount in fantasy drafts this coming season.

There appeared to be times last season in which Kaprizov was struggling, but he still managed to finish with 46 goals and 96 points in 75 games. He was particularly effective late in the year, posting 33 points in Minnesota's final 21 games. Even if Kaprizov is struggling at even strength, he's a lock for production because of his massive power-play role. He averaged 4:10 per game with the man advantage a season ago and finished with a career-best 41 points a man up. Over the past three years, Kaprizov has 104 power-play points. A legitimate threat to crack the 100-point barrier in any given year, Kaprizov is a late first-round option in all fantasy formats this coming year.

In his age-32 season, his ninth in the NHL and fifth with the Rangers, Panarin set new career-best marks in goals (49), points (120) and power-play points (44). The increase in production was the direct result of Panarin shooting the puck way more than ever. After firing just 204 pucks on goal in 2022-23, the Bread Man upped that number to 303 shots on goal this past season. Panarin played the nearly the entire year with veteran Vincent Trocheck and youngster Alexis Lafreniere and the unit was unstoppable. It would be shocking if head coach Peter Laviolette didn't go back to the trio this coming year. Panarin's role on a strong even-strength line and top power-play unit on one of the NHL's best teams is assured, and he is a late first-round option in fantasy formats this coming fall.

Hughes led all NHL defensemen in scoring in his age-24 season, posting 92 points in 82 games. Hughes scored 17 goals after managing just 18 goals in 210 games over the course of the prior three seasons combined. Hughes is also an elite power-play option, as he has 103 points with the man advantage over the last three years. His 8.5 shooting percentage was considerably higher than anything we saw from him in the past, so prepare for that number to dip in 2024-25, but his massive usage, particularly with the man advantage, makes him an extremely safe fantasy option. Expect Hughes to be a top-10 rearguard off the board in drafts this coming fall.

Tkachuk's 2023-24 season was a mixed bag. He set new career-best marks in goals (37) and shots on goal (357), but his assist numbers were way down, which is why he managed just 74 points after finishing with 83 the year prior. As always, Tkachuk was difference maker in leagues which value hits, as he posted 294 of them, his highest mark since 2019-20. Set to play this entire upcoming season at age 25 and locked into a major role on a still-rebuilding team, Tkachuk should again threaten the point-per-game mark this coming season, which combined with his ability to contribute in the  secondary categories makes him worthy of an early-round pick on draft day.

Not surprisingly, the reports of Hedman's demise were greatly exaggerated. Fresh off a year in which he posted a measly 49 points in 76 games, Hedman rebounded to the tune of 76 points in 78 games in 2023-24. The main reason for the resurgence was the fact he regained his role as the quarterback of Tampa Bay's No. 1 power-play unit. Hedman averaged just 2:36 with the man advantage two seasons ago, but that number rose to 3:28 per game this past year. With Mikhail Sergachev traded to Utah, Hedman should receive all the playing time his aging body can handle, making him a no-doubt No. 1 fantasy rearguard this coming season.

A locked-in No. 1 fantasy forward, Nylander is fresh off a season in which he tallied exactly 40 goals for a second straight year, in addition to posting a career-best 98 points, including a whopping 35 with the man advantage. Nylander added 316 shots on goal while averaging 19:55 of ice time per game, his highest mark to date. Nylander has missed just one game during the past three regular seasons, although it's certainly worth noting he sat out three games in the postseason this past April with a migraine issue. The Swede is worthy of the high selection it will cost to draft him this coming fall.

A year after he exploded to the tune of 76 points in 78 games, Morrissey proved his breakout 2022-23 campaign was no fluke. The Calgary native posted 69 points in 81 games a season ago despite the fact his shooting percentage dropped to 5.1 percent, his lowest mark in the past three years, and his power-play production dipped to just 19 points, a far cry from the 29 he posted two seasons ago. In addition to his offensive production, Morrissey is always good for roughly 100 hits and blocked shots in a single year, giving him significant value in all formats. Select Morrissey with confidence as a high-end No. 1 fantasy rearguard on draft day.

Connor was sidelined for a month beginning in mid-December with a knee injury, but still managed to pot 30-plus goals (34) for the sixth time in the past seven years. Connor has been unable to replicate his 47-goal, 93-point 2021-22 form over the course of the past two seasons, but that said, a perennial 30-goal scorer that averages upwards of a point-per-game every single year has a boatload of fantasy value regardless. Still just entering his prime at 27 years of age, Connor would appear to be one of the safer early-to-mid-round selections in fantasy hockey this coming fall.

Father Time remains undefeated, and he got to Ovechkin, at least to some extent, a year ago. The Great Eight posted 30-plus goals (31) for the 18th time in 19 NHL seasons, but he went extremely long stretches without impacting the game at times, something you would never see from Ovechkin in his prime seasons. The good news is Ovechkin managed 28 power-play points, 272 shots on goals and 162 hits, so he was valuable in formats which value secondary statistics. Set to turn 39 in September, Ovechkin is a lock to retain a key role for the Capitals considering it appears the team's only goal in the immediate future is to help him break Wayne Gretzky's record for most goals in NHL history. Just make sure you don't overpay for past production on draft day.

Fox missed nearly all of November with a lower-body injury and was essentially playing on one leg by the time the playoffs rolled around, but he was his usual productive self when healthy, averaging more than a point per game (73 points in 72 games) for the first time in his career. His 17 goals were a new high-water mark, while his 33 points with the man advantage tied his total from the 2021-22 campaign. Fox offers little in terms of hits and blocked shots, but the scoring will always be there, as will an excellent plus-minus rating. Fox's worst rating in his five NHL seasons is plus-18. The 26-year-old rearguard is a No. 1 fantasy defenseman in all formats and among the safest options at the position.

Nothing went right for the Devils a season ago and the health of Hughes was no exception. Jack was an elite fantasy option when in the lineup, posting 27 goals and 74 points in 62 games. He added a whopping 31 points with the man advantage and had 274 shots on goal. They're insane numbers over the course of a full 82-game campaign, but Hughes dealt with multiple ailments during the year, including a shoulder issue which required surgery and ended his year early. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 23, Hughes doesn't project to come at much of a discount on draft day despite the time missed. That said, he's going to be worth the investment if he's able to remain healthy.

All in all, Bedard's rookie season went about how many expected. He missed five weeks in the middle of the year with a broken jaw, but was a solid, if not elite, fantasy option when healthy, finishing with 22 goals, 61 points, 206 shots on goal, and 21 power-play points in 68 games. Of course, playing for one of the worst teams in the NHL has its drawbacks, as evidenced by Bedard's horrific minus-44 rating. Set to play the entirety of the upcoming season at age 19, Bedard is most definitely a candidate for increased offensive production, but the woeful plus-minus rating is likely here to stay, at least for a few more years. Keep that in mind if your league values such numbers.

The Maple Leafs continue to struggle in the playoffs, but Marner continues to be an elite regular-season point producer. He finished with 26 goals and 85 points in 69 games last season, the sixth straight year he has averaged north of a point-per-game. Marner also tallied 25-plus power-play points (27) for a third consecutive campaign. The big story heading into the 2024-25 season will be Marner's expiring contract. He will be an unrestricted free agent next summer and trade chatter will continue until the situation is resolved one way or another. Regardless, Marner is a worthy second-round pick in all fantasy formats this fall.

The picture of consistency, Seider finished with exactly 42 points for a second straight year, while adding a career-high nine goals. The arrival of Shayne Gostisbehere resulted in Seider's power-play timing dropping from 3:06 per game in 2022-23 to 2:16 per game a season ago, but Seider still managed 17 points with the man advantage. Toss in career-best marks in both hits (211) and blocked shots (213) and you have a high-end all-around fantasy asset. Still just 23 years old, Seider is a legitimate No. 1 fantasy rearguard in formats which value hits and blocks and a solid mid-round asset in those which don't.

Guentzel split last season between Pittsburgh and Carolina, finishing with 30 goals and 77 points in 67 regular-season games. He would have set new career-best marks across the board had he not missed about a month late in the year with an upper-body injury. Guentzel was also his usual productive self with the man advantage, posting at least 22 power-play points (22) for a third straight season. Highly sought after in free agency, Guentzel signed a seven-year, $63 million deal with Tampa Bay. He's likely to play alongside Nikita Kucherov and Brayden Point on the Lightning's top line and first power-play unit, giving Guentzel a ridiculous amount of fantasy upside for the 2024-25 campaign.

Skating on Tampa Bay's top line and top power-play unit, Point was his usual productive self despite the fact his team appears to be trending in the wrong direction. Point posted 90-plus points (90) for a second straight campaign, while hitting the 40-goal plateau (46) for the third time in his career. His 32 power-play points were also a new high-water mark. Of concern were Point's minus-16 rating and 20.3 shooting percentage. Any significant dip in the latter category would make Point more of a 35-40 goal guy than 45-plus. Keep that in mind on draft day.

Taking over as Edmonton's full-time power-play quarterback last season, Bouchard averaged more than a point-per-game (82 points in 81 games) and finished fourth among NHL defenders in scoring behind only Quinn Hughes, Cale Makar and Roman Josi. That's elite company. Bouchard added 35 points with the man advantage and finished with 220 shots on goals, placing him behind only Josi, Makar and Rasmus Dahlin among rearguards. Bouchard's hit (71) and blocked shot (105) totals last season are middling for a defender, but that's irrelevant when you're scoring at this pace. Bouchard is a No. 1 fantasy defender in all formats heading into the upcoming season.

Drafted as a No. 1 fantasy defender on the heels of his 22-goal, 74-point 2022-23 campaign, Hamilton played in each of New Jersey's first 20 games last season (five goals, 16 points) before suffering a pectoral injury which ended his year. Having been long eliminated from playoff contention, there was no reason for the club or player to try to rush back. Almost certain to be full strength for training camp, Hamilton is back in the same position as a year ago, locked in as the unquestioned power-play quarterback for a Devils team that is among the more talented offensive groups in the league. He's worth gambling on in fantasy leagues due to the massive upside.

Attempting to make the playoffs with one of the weakest rosters in recent memory, the Capitals had no choice but to lean on Carlson early and often a season ago. He averaged 25:54 of ice time per game, leading the NHL in that category at age 34. Offensively, Carlson tallied 50-plus points (52) for the sixth time in his career, while adding 20-plus power-play points (21) for a sixth time, as well. Betting on aging rearguards is a risky proposition, but Carlson should have a near-identical role in 2024-25 to what we saw a season ago, making him a solid selection for any fantasy manager looking for scoring from the blue line.

Hischier missed about a month early in the year with an upper-body issue but returned in late November and remained healthy the rest of the way. He averaged upwards of a point per game (27 goals, 67 points in 71 games) for a second straight season. All in all, it was a productive year for the Devils captain considering how much time star teammates Jack Hughes and Dougie Hamilton missed due to injury. Hischier is by no means a league-winner from a fantasy perspective, but he's locked into a major role on a team with a boatload of talent offensive players. That makes him worthy of a mid-round pick in all formats for the 2024-25 campaign.

The most important player for the Stanley Cup Champion Panthers, Barkov is fresh off a fourth straight year in which he averaged north of a point-per-game (23 goals, 80 points in 73 games). He added 29 power-play points and 104 hits, the latter of which feels like an outlier given the fact Barkov had never had more than 52 hits in any of his first ten years in the league. Oh, Barkov also won the Selke Trophy as the best defensive forward in the NHL for a second time. The Finn is a lock to produce early-round fantasy value when healthy, but keep in mind Barkov has missed a minimum of nine regular season games each of the past three seasons.

Miller has seemingly come out of nowhere the past three seasons to develop into one of the best offensive players in the NHL, and he is fresh off what was by far his best campaign to date. Miller set new career-best marks in goals (37), points (103), plus-minus (plus-32), power-play points (40) and hits (217) in 2023-24. The 103 points placed him ninth in the NHL in scoring. If your format values hits, there's absolutely a case to be made that Miller should be a first-round pick. If that's not enough, Miller has missed just four regular-season games over the past three years. Invest with confidence on draft day.

Centering superstar winger Artemi Panarin and locked into a role on New York's vaunted No. 1 power-play unit, Trocheck posted 25 goals and a career-best 77 points in 82 games a season ago. His success carried over to the postseason, as Trocheck added eight goals and 20 points in 16 playoff appearances. Trocheck finished with 24 points with the man advantage and chipped in 175 hits, the third straight season he's reached such a number. In addition to his offensive production, Trocheck has been exceedingly durable, missing just one regular-season game the past three years. The Pittsburgh native makes for a fine No. 2 fantasy center come draft day.

Playing the entirety of his second NHL season at age 21, Sanderson had another productive year despite all the dysfunction around him. He finished with a career-best 10 goals and 38 points in 79 games, including 14 points with the man advantage. The fact Sanderson managed to post a plus-8 rating illustrates how well he played. He certainly can take another step forward offensively, and the trade of Jakob Chychrun to the Capitals paves the path to more power-play time to make that happen for Sanderson. As is, he should be viewed as a useful No. 3-4 fantasy defender with the potential for more.

The days of getting Dobson at any sort of discount on draft day have come and gone. The dynamic young defender finished last season with career-best marks in assists (60 in 79 games), points (70), plus-minus (plus-12), average time on ice (24:31), power-play points (24), hits (84) and blocked shots (180). Not only has the 24-year-old been an excellent player, but he's remained healthy, missing just nine regular season games over the past three seasons combined. Dobson appears fully capable of a repeat performance in 2024-25, making him a low-end No. 1 fantasy defenseman on draft day.

Larkin missed a decent chunk of time a season ago due to injury but managed to average north of a point-per-game (69 points in 68 games) for the first time in his career. His 33 goals were a new career high, while Larkin added 26 points with the man advantage. It was reported in late June that Larkin underwent offseason surgery for an upper-body ailment, but he is expected to be fine for training camp. Locked into a massive role as Detroit's No. 1 center, Larkin should once again be worthy of an early-round selection in fantasy drafts this coming fall.

Those that spent a second-round pick on Stutzle in fantasy drafts a year ago ended up getting burned in a major way. Fresh off his 39-goal, 90-point breakout 2022-23 campaign, Stutzle came tumbling back to Earth last season. He managed just 18 goals and 70 points in 75 games. That's the bad news. The good news is that Stutzle posted 20-plus power-play points (20) for a third straight year and is due major positive regression in the shooting percentage department after just 9.4 percent of his shots went in, down from 17.1 percent two seasons ago. Still just 22 years old, Stutzle looks like a prime rebound candidate, even if he is unable to get to the same levels as two years ago.

Montour missed the first month-plus of last season with a shoulder injury. He debuted in mid-November and played in every game for Florida the rest of the way, including their entire run to the Stanley Cup. Montour's offensive production was way down. He managed just eight goals and 33 points in 66 games. Clearly not deterred by the lack of scoring, the Kraken inked Montour to a seven-year contract on July 1 worth a shade under $50 million. Montour should join Vince Dunn on Seattle's top power-play unit, making him a reasonable middle-round selection in fantasy drafts this fall.

One of the few players in the NHL that has gotten noticeably better in the latter stages of his career, Kreider continued his torrid production a season ago. He posted 39 goals and 75 points, including 29 with the man advantage, in 82 games in 2023-24. Kreider's string of 10 straight seasons with 100 hits was snapped, however, as he finished with 99. Kreider turned 33 in late April. It's dangerous betting on an aging power forward, but he should once again be able to return mid-round fantasy value given his role on both the Rangers' top line and top power-play unit.

The days of Tavares carrying fantasy teams to the promised land have come and gone, but he's still proven to be a reliable mid-round asset in the latter stages of his career. He posted 29 goals and 65 points (including 20 with the man advantage) in 80 games a season ago, perfectly reasonable numbers for the 33-year-old. With one more year on his contract at a cap hit of $11 million, the Maple Leafs and Tavares are stuck with each other for the 2024-25 campaign. Tavares is at risk of seeing his role reduced in what will likely be his final year with the club, but it's difficult to see it changing all that much. As a result, Tavares should again be good for roughly 25 goals and 60 points this coming year.

The new face of the Utah Hockey Club, Keller, fresh off his second straight 30-goal (33) season, will help spearhead the move from Arizona to Salt Lake City. Keller was once again by far the best player on the former Coyotes team last season, as he posted 76 points, including 30 with the man advantage, in addition to a career-best 228 shots on goal in 78 games. Keller offers nothing in terms of hits or blocked shots, and his plus-minus rating is typically poor, so while he would appear to be a lock for early-round offensive production, he offers little in terms of secondary fantasy scoring. Keep that in mind on draft day.

Zibanejad's shooting percentage tumbled to 11.8 percent last season, his worst since the 2016-17 campaign, and his production suffered mightily as a result. He scored just 26 times in 81 games, a woeful total given the fact he tallied 68 times in 163 over the prior two seasons. The lone bit of good news is that Zibanejad's power-play production remained exceptional, as he finished with 30-plus points (31) with the man advantage for a second straight year. Zibanejad's role is worth monitoring during training camp. The Rangers appear committed to elevating rising youngster Alexis Lafreniere to their No. 1 power-play unit for the 2024-25 season and if that is indeed the case, Zibanejad could be the guy that sees his role decreased as a result.

Pettersson is fresh off a strange season. His scoring numbers were down (34 goals, 89 points in 82 games) compared to two years ago (39 goals, 102 points in 80 games), but his shooting percentage went up to 16.4 percent and he added six additional power-play points, finishing with 31. There were some minor rumblings about a potential trade if Pettersson wouldn't agree to a new contract, but he ended up signing an eight-year, $92.8 million deal in March. Still just 25 years old (26 in November), Pettersson is a low-end No. 1 fantasy center and should be drafted as such this coming year.

Verhaeghe took a slight step back from his 42-goal, 73-point breakout season two years ago, but still managed to post 34 goals and 72 points in 76 games while helping lead the Panthers to the Stanley Cup. Verhaeghe's usage with the man advantage was way up. He finished with 21 power-play points after posting just 19 in his first four NHL seasons combined. Set to player the entirety of this upcoming year at age 29, Verhaeghe seems primed for another high-end offensive season given his top-six role for one of the best teams in the league. That makes him a worthy selection in all fantasy formats this coming fall.

Trouba was his usual dependable self in the hits (191) and blocked shots (183) department a season ago but otherwise had arguably his worst year to date. He managed just 22 points in 69 games and was relegated to third-pairing duties during what was a horrendous postseason performance. The Rangers reportedly gave serious consideration to trying to move Trouba this offseason, but were unable to get a deal done, perhaps due to Trouba's partial no-trade clause. As it stands now, it appears the captain will return to Gotham next season, at which point he will only be a fantasy option in leagues which value hits and blocks.

The Devils handed Bratt a new eight-year, $63 million deal last June and he responded with 27 goals and a career-high 83 points in 82 games. It marked the second straight year in which Bratt hadn't missed a regular season game. His 27 points with the man advantage were a new high-water mark, as were Bratt's 248 shots on goal. The Swede's offensive production was particularly impressive when you consider running mate Jack Hughes missed 20 games due to injury. Hughes should be back to full health in 2024-25, which combined with the return of Dougie Hamilton should allow Bratt to threaten the 90-point barrier for the first time in his NHL career.

Signed to a seven-year, $59.5 million contract extension just days before the start of last season, Scheifele posted 25 goals and 72 points in 74 games, his highest point total since the 2019-20 campaign. He added 18 power-play points, while his plus-19 rating was tied for the best mark of his career. All told, Scheifele has averaged more than a point per game the past eight seasons. The unquestioned top pivot in Winnipeg, the Jets need Scheifele to continue to score at that pace if they hope to have success as a team in 2024-25. Scheifele again projects as a rock-solid mid-round fantasy selection in all formats.

Having never scored more than 36 goals in any of his first eight years in the NHL, Hyman broke out to the tune of 54 goals in 80 games a season ago. That placed him third in the league behind only Auston Matthews and Sam Reinhart. While the goals went up, Hyman's assist total was way down, and as a result, he managed just 77 points in 80 games after posting 83 points in 79 games the year prior. Hyman is a lock for high-end production given his role on Edmonton's top power-play unit, but keep in mind his 18.6 percent shooting percentage last season was his highest mark since the 2019-20 campaign. If that number regresses to the mean in 2024-25, Hyman is likely in line for closer to 40 goals than the 54 we saw in his breakout campaign.

DeBrincat came out on fire in his first season in Detroit, posting nine goals and 13 points in his first seven games with his new club. It was a gigantic struggle the rest of the way. DeBrincat closed with 27 goals and 67 points in 82 games, virtually identical numbers to his lone season in Ottawa. The biggest concern was the lack of power-play production. Averaging just 2:54 per game a man up, down more than a minute from the year prior, DeBrincat managed just 19 power-play points after posting no fewer than 28 the previous two years. DeBrincat has health on his side, having not missed a game since 2020-21, but he seems to have settled in as a 30-goal guy with limited upside beyond that.

Eriksson Ek's offensive role continued to grow for the Wild a season ago, as he finished with new career-high marks in goals (30), points (64), shots on goal (267), average time on ice (20:32) and hits (169). Eriksson Ek added 20-plus power-play points (21) for the second straight year, as well. The eight-year, $42 million deal Eriksson Ek signed with Minnesota in July 2021 seemed like a overpay at the time, but the organization clearly knew what they were doing, as the big Swede has developed into a crucial player for the club. Given his significant usage, Eriksson Ek should have no issues repeating his offensive numbers from a season ago in the 2024-25 campaign.

The Blues got 31 goals and 67 points in 82 games from Kyrou a season ago, a slight step backwards from his numbers the prior two years, but roughly the same level of production. His minus-12 rating was nothing to write home about but was a massive improvement from the minus-38 rating Kyrou posted in 2022-23. Kyrou's 12.4 shooting percentage was his lowest mark in four years, so he's due some positive regression in that area. Kyrou may struggle for a true breakout season while playing for a middling team in St. Louis, but he should receive enough ice time to return mid-round fantasy value this coming season.

Boldy is fresh off a solid, if unspectacular year. A nice surge late in the season helped him finish with 29 goals and career-high 69 points (25 on the power-play) in 75 games a season ago, similar numbers to his second-year breakout campaign. The good news is that Boldy will play almost the entirety of this upcoming season at age 23 and there's a real chance for increased production. As is, Boldy is a huge part of both the present and future for the Wild and a rock-solid mid-round fantasy pick on draft day.

Bennett was banged up a good chunk of last season, appearing in just 69 of Florida's 82 regular season games. He was again effective when in the lineup, posting 20 goals, 41 points, 100 penalty minutes and 171 shots on goal, in addition to career-best marks in power-play points (12) and hits (173). There's reason to believe Bennett could be a mid-round fantasy asset if he is able to remain healthy for an entire year. Just keep in mind he's played no more than 71 games in any of the past three seasons.
