No player in the NHL had worse injury luck last season than Sergachev. He missed more than a month starting in late December with a lower-body injury, returned for an early February game against the Rangers, and immediately broke his tibia and fibula following a fluke collision with Alexis Lafreniere. To Sergachev's credit, he worked his tail off to return and made it back for Tampa's final two games of their first-round series loss to the Panthers. All told, Sergachev had 19 points in 34 games. His reward? An offseason trade to Utah. The move may be a blessing in disguise from a fantasy standpoint, as Sergachev will finally serve as an unquestioned No. 1 defender for the first time in his career. His fantasy arrow is pointing upward, as long as the injury bug doesn't bite again.

Appearing in all 82 games for the Red Wings last season, Raymond did his best to single-handedly drag his team to the postseason. He posted a career-best 31 goals and 72 points, including six goals and 11 points in his final six games. Truly remarkable stuff from a player that turned just 22 years old in late March. Detroit has plenty of other talented offensive players in the likes of Dylan Larkin, Patrick Kane, Alex DeBrincat and Vladimir Tarasenko, but no player on their roster can match the combination of youth and future upside that Raymond brings to the table.

McAvoy had a solid, if unspectacular season. He finished with a career-best 12 goals, along with 47 points in 74 games. McAvoy had just 13 points with the man advantage, but his 3:14 power-play ice time per game was his highest to date, so he seems likely to rebound in that category this coming year. Playing for one of the best teams in the NHL, McAvoy has been a plus player all seven years of his career. Toss in career-best marks in both hits (159) and blocked shots (159) and you have a solid all-around fantasy asset. McAvoy should again produce enough to be targeted as a low-end No. 2 fantasy defender in 2024-25.

Werenski was about the lone Blue Jacket that lived up to expectations from a fantasy standpoint a season ago. He posted 11 goals and a career-high 57 points in 70 games. Werenski also finished with an even plus-minus rating, no small task considering the heavy minutes he logged on one of the worst teams in the NHL. The fact Werenski scored that much considering he managed just 12 points with the man advantage is extremely impressive. Werenski is a major injury risk given his history, but he projects as a legitimate No. 2 fantasy defender for as long as he can remain in the lineup.

Meier's first full season in New Jersey got off to a dreadful start. He missed two weeks in the middle of November with a lower-body injury and didn't register a single point in nine games upon returning. He was a bit better the rest of the way, ultimately finishing with 28 goals and 52 points in 69 games, to go along with a career-worst minus-28 rating. If that wasn't bad enough, Meier underwent offseason shoulder surgery, but he is expected to be fully ready for training camp. The Devils have a boatload of talented offensive players, giving new head coach Sheldon Keefe plenty of options when it comes to his lineup. Meier should be available at a discount in fantasy drafts this fall, making him a reasonable bounce-back option for those searching for a value pick.

Faber was a lifesaver for the Wild a season ago, as the 21-year-old took on a massive role for the club, posting eight goals and 47 points in 82 games while averaging 24:58 of ice time per game, sixth most in the entire league. Faber was recognized for his excellent freshman year, as he was named a finalist for the Calder Trophy for NHL Rookie of the Year, an award won by Chicago's Connor Bedard. Toss in Faber's 16 power-play points, 136 shots on goal, 65 hits and 150 blocked shots and you have high-end all-around production. Given how young he is, it's reasonable to expect Faber to take another step forward this coming season, making him a player to target in all fantasy formats.

From a fantasy standpoint, Pionk has quickly and quietly developed into one of the most dependable rearguards in the NHL. He's finished between 32-34 points each of the past four seasons. He's also always good for about 10 power-play points and roughly 140 shots on goal. Those numbers won't do much for you in standard formats, but Pionk's contributions a season ago in both the hits (220) and blocked shots (118) categories give him significant value in leagues which value such numbers. The upside here is limited as long as stud Winnipeg rearguard Josh Morrissey remains healthy, but there's a place for Pionk on your roster depending on your settings.

Marchand's first season in the post-Patrice Bergeron era was solid, if unspectacular. He appeared in all 82 games for the Bruins, posting 29 goals and 67 points, numbers like what we saw from him a year prior, albeit in nine extra games. Marchand was his usual productive self with the man advantage, posting 25-plus (26) power-play points for a third straight year. Marchand is locked into a top-six role with Boston moving forward, but at 36 years of age and having taken a ton of physical punishment over the years, the Bruins' captain is more of a floor option than ceiling option from a fantasy standpoint.

Nurse's offensively production dipped considerably a season ago. He had just 32 points in 81 games, his lowest mark since the 2017-18 campaign. Nurse doesn't see much power-play time anymore with Evan Bouchard and Mattias Ekholm around, so he must do his damage at even strength. On a more positive note, Nurse was his usual physical self, posting a whopping 168 hits and 172 blocked shots, while finishing with a plus rating (plus-3) for a fourth straight year. Nurse needs to be rostered in all formats which value hits and blocks, but you can probably find a better option in standard formats on draft day.

Regression hit McCann in a major way in the shooting percentage department, as he finished at a 13.4 percent mark last season, a far cry from the 19 percent he fired at in his 2022-23 breakout campaign. As a result, McCann's goal total dropped from 40 to 29. That's the bad news. The good news is that he finished with 23 power-play points and 216 shots on goal, both of which were new career highs. McCann appears to be a lock to finish with 25-plus goals and 60-plus points this coming year; just make sure you aren't paying for past production on draft day.

Jones was a true workhorse for Chicago last season, averaging 25:29 of ice time per game, fourth-most in the entire league. He managed eight goals and 31 points in 67 games, including nine points with the man advantage. Jones' minus-15 rating, while ugly, was light years better than the minus-38 he posted two years ago. Jones also posted 77 hits and 131 blocked shots, the eighth year in a row he's exceeded 100 blocks. With the Blackhawks taking steps to be more competitive in 2024-25, Jones is a sneaky candidate for increased production. Don't forget about him on draft day.

Reilly had a strange season. His production (seven goals, 58 points in 72 games) was fine, but he averaged just 2:39 per game with the man advantage, his lowest mark in the past four years. Somehow, he still managed 20 power-play points. The good news is there doesn't appear to be anyone on Toronto's roster to threaten Rielly's status as the quarterback on their vaunted No. 1 power-play unit. The 30-year-old rearguard should be drafted as a No. 2 fantasy defender for the upcoming campaign.

A year after playing in just 45 games due to injury, Ehlers appeared in all 82 regular-season games for the Jets a season ago. He was his usual productive self, finishing with 25 goals and 61 points. Ehlers' upside may be somewhat limited, but he's seemingly a lock for 25 goals and 60 points every single season and there's fantasy value in that. The question at this point is whether he will spend the entirety of the upcoming year in Winnipeg. Ehlers is in the final year of his contract and due to become an unrestricted free agent next summer. It's a situation worth monitoring.

Parayko tallied 10 goals last season, his most since the 2019-20 campaign, but his assist totals were way down, and as a result he managed just 26 points, his lowest mark in the past three years. The lone bit of good news is that Parayko once again contributed in secondary categories. He had 154 shots on goal, 113 hits, and a career-best 218 blocked shots. Now 31 years old, Parayko has topped 30 points just once in the past six years. He's only an option in leagues which value hits and blocks.

Turns out it was too soon to label Lafreniere a bust. The No. 1 overall pick from 2020 took a significant step forward during his fourth season in the league, posting 28 goals and 57 points in 82 games. He was even better in the playoffs, posting eight goals and 14 points in 16 appearances. As well as Lafreniere played alongside Artemi Panarin and Vincent Trocheck last season, it's difficult to see him taking another step forward offensively unless he is elevated to New York's loaded No. 1 power-play unit. Lafreniere, along with defenseman Adam Fox and goaltender Igor Shesterkin are clearly the future of the franchise, so an increased role in 2024-25 is certainly not out of the question.

Not much went right for Ottawa last season, but Batherson was his usual productive self. He set new career-best marks in both goals (28) and points (66) while playing in all 82 games for a second straight year. Although Batherson added 20-plus power-play points (22) once again, his average time on ice a man up dropped from 3:52 per game in 2022-23 to 3:03 per game last season. That's something to keep an eye on moving forward, as Batherson's production will likely dip over the long term if the change is permanent. As is, Batherson is a safe pick in the latter rounds and a solid source of secondary scoring in all fantasy formats.

Injury and a personal matter limited Zuccarello to just 69 games a season ago, but he was his usual productive self when in the lineup, posting 12 goals and 63 points. His 33 power-play points were a new career-best mark. It's not very often you see a player post these types of offensive numbers in their 14th NHL season. Betting on a guy that will play the entirety of this upcoming year at age 37 is risky business, but Zuccarello has shown no real signs of slowing down. Fantasy managers should be able to squeeze mid-round fantasy value out of the Norwegian for at least one more season.

Hagel continues to go about his business, providing solid second-line production for the Lightning despite not receiving a ton of fanfare. He had 26 goals and a career-high 75 points in 82 games last season. The fact his scoring numbers went way up was remarkable considering Hagel managed just seven power-play points, nearly half of the 13 posted two years ago. Hagel always seems to get his numbers despite the fact Lightning head coach Jon Cooper moves him all around the lineup. That should continue in 2024-25, making Hagel a worthy late-round fantasy pick in all formats.

Strome is very quietly fresh off the best season of his NHL career. Appearing in all 82 games, he set new high-water marks in goals (27), points (67), shots on goal (169), power-play points (22) and average ice time (17:57). The Capitals added Pierre-Luc Dubois and Andrew Mangiapane to their forward group this offseason in an attempt to be more competitive, so it's easy to envision a scenario in which Strome sees his usage drop in 2024-25. He should still be worthy of a late-round pick in most formats, but a repeat performance is far from guaranteed.

Boeser had been up and down during his Vancouver career, but the recently completed campaign was his first true breakout season. He set new career-best marks in goals (40), points (73) and power-play points (25). His 204 shots on goal were Boeser's most since the 2018-19 season. He added a dozen points in 12 postseason appearances before a blood-clotting issue ended his year prematurely. It obviously has the potential to be a serious long-term issue, so fantasy managers should look for an update on Boeser's status prior to the start of training camp. If he's given the green light, Boeser should again be a nice source of secondary scoring in all formats this fall.

Horvat's eight-year, $68 million deal went into effect prior to last season and the Islanders received a nice return on their investment. Horvat posted 33 goals and 68 points in 81 games in his first full season with the team, in addition to adding 18 points with the man advantage. Horvat's 248 shots on goal were a new career-high and his 13.3 percent shooting percentage was his lowest mark in the past four years, so he could be due some positive regression in that category in 2024-25. The Islanders are not a team to target from a fantasy perspective, but Horvat's usage is so great that he should again have no issues carving out mid-round value this coming year.

Faulk was banged up a good portion of last season, appearing in just 60 of St. Louis' 82 regular-season games. He posted 30 points and managed just two goals, although the latter number was the direct result of a woeful and unsustainable 1.5 percent shooting percentage. For comparison's sake, Faulk's previous career-low in that category was 3.3 percent. Even with the positive regression likely forthcoming, Faulk is now 32 years old and plays for a mediocre team, and his power-play role is not guaranteed. Toss in all of those factors with the recent injury history and you can probably do better on draft day.

Lindholm's game has been trending in the wrong direction the past two years. He split last season between Calgary and Vancouver, finishing with 15 goals and 44 points in 75 games. He had just 12 power-play points, his lowest total in six years, and posted an ugly minus-14 rating. Clearly not deterred, the Bruins handed Lindholm a seven-year, $54.25 million contract on July 1. The financial commitment suggests Boston is intent on handing the Swede a massive role moving forward, although Lindholm seems unlikely to threaten the 40-goal and point-per-game marks we saw during his best years with the Flames.

Buoyed by a 13.6 shooting percentage on a career-best 272 shots on goal, Vatrano finished with 37 goals in 82 games last season. He had never scored more than 24 goals in any of his first eight years in the league. His assist total remained low, as always, so Vatrano managed just 60 points in addition to an ugly minus-20 rating. The 30-year-old Massachusetts native would seem to be an especially poor bet to repeat those type of numbers in 2024-25. The Ducks will be looking to get their countless talented young players more involved, which means Vatrano's playing time, particularly with the man advantage, is likely to fall. Vatrano is a reasonable late-round depth pick, but don't pay for past production.

One of the steadiest and most underrated offensive players in the league the last few years, Nelson is fresh off his third straight 30-goal (34) season. His 250 shots on goal and 19 power-play points were both career-best marks in his age-32 season. Nelson has gotten considerably more productive in the latter stages of his career. Entering the final year of his contract before hitting unrestricted free agency in the summer of 2025, Nelson will again fill a top-six role for the Islanders, in addition to occupying a spot on their top power-play unit, making him a worthy late-round pick in all formats this coming fall.

Giroux appeared in all 82 games once again last season, but his scoring numbers were way down. He managed just 21 goals and 64 points, a far cry from the 35 goals and 79 points he posted a year prior. Giroux's minus-14 rating was his worst mark since the 2016-17 season, while his 19 power-play points were his second-lowest total in the past 12 years. Giroux is locked into a top-six role for the Senators, but it wouldn't be the least bit surprising for Ottawa to give an increased role to Josh Norris or Shane Pinto this coming year. The 36-year-old Giroux is a riskier fantasy pick than ever this coming fall.

Nugent-Hopkins' career-best 104-point season back in 2022-23 seemed like a fluke at the time, and a year later, that almost certainly seems to be the case. He came crashing down to Earth a year ago, finishing with 18 goals and 67 points in 80 games, numbers more in line with what he had produced earlier in his career. RNH managed just 26 points with the man advantage, less than half of the 53 he tallied in his breakout campaign. Nugent-Hopkins is a good player and locked into a major role on a loaded offense, so he has plenty of fantasy value, but he's more of a secondary scoring option than a core piece for drafters this coming fall.

Rossi finally took on a full-time role for the Wild last season and had a nice year. He appeared in all 82 games, finishing with 21 goals and 40 points. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 23, Rossi is theoretically a candidate for further production, but he would likely have to see an increased role with the man advantage for it to happen. Based on Minnesota's current personnel, that seems unlikely. Don't overpay for a breakout that is unlikely to materialize for at least another season.

Seeing a larger role in his second full season with the Wild, Middleton averaged a career-high 19:49 of ice time per game. The additional responsibility resulted in new career-best marks in goals (seven), assists (18), points (25), PIM (77), hits (147) and blocked shots (161). Clearly impressed with his efforts, Minnesota inked Middleton to a four-year, $17.4 million contract extension in July. The monetary commitment suggests the 28-year-old should occupy a top-four role for the club moving forward, but Middleton is only a fantasy option in the deepest of leagues which value hits and blocks.

Guenther joined the then-Coyotes in early January and appeared in each of the club's final 45 regular-season games. He was a legitimate difference-maker from an offensive perspective, posting 18 goals and 35 points, including 13 with the man advantage, in his limited run. The production was exceptional when you consider Guenther didn't turn 21 until this past April. One of the most valuable long-term assets Utah has at its disposal, Guenther has the look of one of the NHL's brighter young stars. This may be the final year you can get him at any sort of discount on draft day.

Wilson was up to his usual antics last season, making life miserable for opposing players while adding some secondary offense for the Capitals. He posted 18 goals and 35 points in 75 games, while finishing with 200-plus hits (228) for the eighth time in the past decade. The Capitals took steps to become more competitive this coming season by adding Pierre-Luc Dubois and Andrew Mangiapane to their forward group via trade. Wilson, now 30 years old and with a ton of miles on his body from a physical standpoint, would seem to be a prime candidate for a role reduction. He's only a fantasy option in deeper formats which value hits.

It's rare to acquire one of the best defenders in the league via waivers, but that's what the Panthers managed to do with Forsling in 2021 and it helped them win the Stanley Cup a season ago. The Swede posted 10 goals and 39 points in 79 regular-season games, in addition to posting a league-best plus-56 rating. Over the course of his four full seasons with the Panthers, Forsling is a plus-133. He is a mid-round fantasy asset regardless, but with Brandon Montour heading to Seattle in free agency, he has a real chance at increased power-play time, making Forsling a clear player to target in drafts this fall.

Dunn was amid arguably the best stretch of his career, posting 45 points in 57 games before an upper-body issue resulted in him missing 19 of Seattle's final 21 contests. There have been no indications the ailment is a long-term concern, but with the Kraken long out of playoff contention, the team opted to play it safe with Dunn late in the year and not rush him back. Dunn played in 81 of 82 games the year prior, so he's not typically an injury risk. With three years left on his deal with a cap hit of $7.35 million, Dunn will be back to resume his role as the quarterback of Seattle's No. 1 power-play unit in 2024-25.

Kane debuted for Detroit in early December and remained healthy the remainder of the season outside of a seven-game stretch in mid-to-late January. He appeared in 50 games, posting 20 goals and 47 points. Kane was his usual productive self with the man advantage, posting 15 power-play points. The future Hall of Famer inked a one-year deal to return to Detroit in the offseason. The days of Kane leading your fantasy team to championships are over, but seemingly back to full health, he should once again push for mid-round value on draft day.

Buchnevich appeared in 80 games for the Blues last season, managing 27 goals and 63 points, his lowest total in the past three years. Buchnevich's 207 shots on goal were a new career-high, so he probably deserved a bit better fate than he received. A solid if unspectacular top-six forward, the main question at this point appears to be where Buchnevich will be playing moving forward. He's been mentioned in trade rumors in the past year and would appear to be a luxury for a St. Louis team in a soft rebuild. The 29-year-old should be good for roughly 30 goals and 70 points should he remain with the Blues this coming season.

Marchenko displayed improvement across the board in his second NHL campaign. He buried 20-plus goals (23) once again, while setting new career-best marks in assists (19), points (42), shots on goal (193) and power-play points (13). Much more of a sniper than playmaker, Marchenko is never going to register many assists, but he's locked into a significant role on a rebuilding team, meaning 30-plus goals appears to be well within the range of outcomes for the 2024-25 campaign.

Cooley played well in his first NHL campaign for the then-Coyotes, posting 20 goals and 44 points in 82 games, placing him fourth among first-year players in scoring. He was named to the All-Rookie Team for his efforts. Cooley added 151 shots on goal and 13 power-play points. Set to play the entirety of his second NHL season at age 20, it's reasonable to expect Cooley to take an additional step forward in terms of production, with 25 goals and 60 points a fair projection for a player with his talent level.

Larsson's offensive upside has always been limited, but he managed just 18 points in 81 games last season, a far cry from the career-best 33 points he posted a year prior. On a more positive note, Larsson was again difference-maker from a physical standpoint, racking up 162 hits and 151 blocked shots. The big Swede also has durability on his side. He's missed just one game the past three seasons and that was for the birth of his child. Larsson isn't a fantasy option in standard formats, but he's a worthy depth option in leagues which value hits and blocks.

Barzal posted 80 points in 80 games a season ago, his most effective campaign since his 2017-18 Calder Trophy-winning season. It was the second time in his career he averaged a point-per-game. Barzal's increased production was simply the result of shooting the puck more than ever. He finished with 240 shots on goal after never posting more than 179 in any one season over the course of his first six years in the league. The Islanders remain a mediocre offensive team, but Barzal is locked into a massive role and will play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 27. There's most definitely a scenario in which he can replicate his success from a year ago.

An odd fit in Ottawa from the very start, Chychrun never looked fully comfortable with the Senators despite the fact he posted 14 goals and 41 points in his lone full season with the club. He ended up splitting power-play time with the likes of Thomas Chabot and Jake Sanderson, although his 16 points with the man advantage were a new high-water mark. From a fantasy standpoint, his July trade to Washington would seem to be a major positive. Chychrun, a lefty, should fit in seamlessly on the club's top power-play unit alongside John Carlson, a righty. Set to play nearly the entirety of this upcoming season at age 26, Chychrun has plenty of upside on draft day.

Lee posted 20 goals for the Islanders last season, the eighth time in his career he's reached that plateau. That's where the good news ends. He finished with just 37 points and his usage was down in a major way. Lee managed just five power-play points and averaged just 1:43 per game with the man advantage. For comparison's sake, Lee had 14 power-play points and averaged 3:05 with the man advantage a year prior. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 34, Lee has virtually no chance of amassing fantasy value barring an unexpected role change.

Hronek picked a great time to have his most productive season to date. Set to enter unrestricted free agency this past July, he posted a career-high 48 points in 81 games for Vancouver a year ago. The scoring increase was surprising given the fact Hronek's role with the man advantage predictably decreased with Norris Trophy winner Quinn Hughes around. Clearly impressed with his efforts, the Canucks inked Hronek to an eight-year, $58 million extension in June. Hronek would be a must-have player should Hughes get injured, but as is, he's more of a mid-to-late round option from a fantasy standpoint.

Playing the entirety of last season at age 24, Thomas had the true breakout season many thought he was capable of. He set new career-best marks in goals (26), assists (60), points (86), power-play points (27) and average time on ice (20:58) while playing in all 82 games for the Blues. His shot on goal numbers, while still low at 170, were considerably better than the 106 shots he fired on net in 73 games two years ago. As is, this would seem to be the ceiling for Thomas. It's impossible to score 30-plus goals every single year unless you're a volume shooter and Thomas has certainly proven to not be that over the course of his NHL career. Just keep that in mind on draft day.

Schenn tallied exactly 20 goals last season, the third straight year he has reached that plateau. That said, his overall scoring numbers took a nosedive. He managed just 46 points in 82 games, including 12 with the man advantage, his lowest marks over that same period of time. Now 33 years old, Schenn added 170 shots on goal and 169 hits, so he contributed in formats which value such numbers, but it seems quite clear he is trending in the wrong direction in the latter stages of his career. You can almost certainly do better on draft day.

Skinner's one-year, $3 million contract with the Oilers can no doubt be classified as a "prove it" deal -- especially considering he was previously earning $9 million AAV before being bought out by the Sabres. The veteran winger's availability came on the heels of a disappointing 2023-24 campaign in which he tallied just 24 goals and 22 helpers, missing the 30-goal mark for the first time since 2020-21. Still, with the move to Edmonton, Skinner should be in the mix for a strong bounce-back campaign playing in a top-six role with either Connor McDavid or Leon Draisaitl. As such, don't be shocked if Skinner pushes for the 40-goal threshold, a mark he has reached just once in his 14-year NHL career.

Spending his first five NHL seasons in Los Angeles, Roy earned a reputation as a steady, middle-pairing defender. He had five goals and 25 points in 81 games for the Kings last season, along with a plus-21 rating, 152 hits, and 197 blocked shots. Impressed with his efforts, the Capitals inked Roy to a six-year, $34.5 million deal in free agency this past summer. He's set up for an increased role with his new club, making Roy a respectable late-round fantasy selection in formats which value hits and blocks, though it remains unlikely for him to see much power-play time.

The No. 2 overall selection in 2023, the Ducks were very careful with Carlsson's usage in his rookie campaign. They gave him frequent days off early in the season and the Swede also missed significant chunks of time with a knee injury and concussion. All told, Carlsson appeared in 55 games, posting 12 goals and 29 points. The long-term upside here is through the roof given Carlsson's draft pedigree and overall abilities, but it may be another season before the 19-year-old manages to put it all together. Carlsson remains a better keeper or dynasty pick than redraft asset.

A victim of the dreaded "sophomore slump," Beniers' production fell off a cliff in his second NHL campaign. A year after posting 24 goals and 57 points and being named Rookie of the Year, Beniers managed just 15 goals and 37 points in 77 games. He received more playing time than ever and shot the puck at a similar clip, so there's no obvious reason for the struggles. Beniers is a bounce-back candidate from a fantasy standpoint if for no other reason than it's impossible to envision a scenario in which he plays so poorly once again.

Miller's scoring numbers were down last season (eight goals, 30 points in 80 games) compared to two years ago (nine goals, 43 points in 79 games), but you're going to get that type of volatility on a year-by-year basis when investing in a rearguard that doesn't see much time with the man advantage. On a more positive note, Miller added 100-plus hits (148) and blocked shots (117) for a second straight season. Still just 24 years old, Miller remains one of the most important defenders for one of the NHL's best teams, but it's simply not a role that produces anything more than late-round fantasy value now.

Teravainen was productive in what would end up being his eighth and final year in Carolina. He potted a career-best 25 goals and finished with 53 points, including 17 with the man advantage, in 76 games. Entering unrestricted free agency this past July, the Finn inked a three-year, $16.2 million deal with the Blackhawks, the team which drafted him and with whom he spent his first three NHL seasons. Teravainen would seem to have an excellent chance of playing alongside Connor Bedard on Chicago's top line, which should allow him to generate sneaky mid-round fantasy value in all formats this coming season.

From a production standpoint, Coyle was arguably the biggest beneficiary from the retirement of Patrice Bergeron. Playing in his twelfth NHL season, Coyle set new career-best marks in goals (25), points (60), power-play points (11) and average time on ice (18:04). He also played in all 82 games for a third straight campaign. Boston's signing of Elias Lindholm in free agency may result in Coyle's numbers taking a bit of a dip, but there should still be enough production to make the 32-year-old worthy of a selection in the latter stages of fantasy drafts this coming fall.

An injury to Dougie Hamilton forced Hughes to take on what was likely a bigger role than the Devils preferred in his first full NHL campaign. He appeared in all 82 games, finishing with nine goals and 47 points, including 25 with the man advantage. Hughes was named to the All-Rookie Team and was a finalist for the Calder Trophy as NHL Rookie of the Year. That said, Hughes is a prime candidate to be overdrafted in fantasy drafts this coming fall. Hamilton is back to quarterback the New Jersey power-play and newcomers Brett Pesce and Brenden Dillon will eat up minutes at even strength. Hughes is a solid fantasy pick, but a further breakout is far from assured.

Always among the league leaders in hits, Gudas amassed a whopping 232 of them a season ago despite appearing in only 66 games for Anaheim. He added six goals, 18 points, and 154 blocked shots for good measure. Set to enter his 13th NHL season, you know what you get from the rugged veteran rearguard. The offensive numbers are always limited, but Gudas is one of the rare few difference-makers in the league when it comes to the hits department. If that's a statistic valued in your format, don't be afraid to draft Gudas with a late-round pick.

Durzi appeared in 76 games last season for the then-Coyotes, posting nine goals and 41 points, including 16 with the man advantage. The numbers were eerily like what Durzi finished with the year prior. Utah was clearly impressed with his efforts, and they inked Durzi to a new four-year, $24 million deal in late June. With Mikhail Sergachev now on board to serve as Utah's No. 1 defenseman, Durzi will slide down the depth chart. His fantasy value will be dependent on whether he remains on the top power-play unit. It's a situation to monitor in training camp.

A model of consistency, Bjorkstrand potted 20 goals last season for the third straight campaign and fifth time in the past six years. He also finished with a career-best 59 points, fueled by his 25 points with the man advantage. That's the good news. The bad news is Bjorkstrand finished with a hideous minus-20 rating and is now a minus-71 combined over the course of the last four seasons. Still just 29 years of age, Bjorkstrand is by no means a league-winner from a fantasy standpoint, but he remains a capable middle-six winger for the Kraken and that gives him some value in deeper formats.

Crouse has quietly developed into a rock-solid middle-six NHL winger. He posted 20-plus goals (23) last season for a third straight year, while posting 40-plus points (42) for a second straight campaign. Crouse's 10 power-play points were a new career-high. He added 175 hits for good measure. He's locked into a significant role for the Utah HC, making Crouse a legitimate mid-to-late round fantasy option in any format which places an additional emphasis on hits. In standard formats, you can do better.

Fowler's 2023-24 season was a mixed bag. Let's start with the good news. He averaged north of 24 minutes per game (24:25) for a third straight year. Fowler was also his usual productive self offensively, posting 39 points in 81 games, including 18 with the man advantage. Now for the bad news. Fowler finished with a horrific minus-36 rating, ninth-worst in the entire NHL. Now 32 years old, Fowler would appear to be at risk of a role reduction given all the young blueliners the Ducks have in their pipeline. He seems like a good bet to provide late-round value for at least one more season, but keep in mind it could all fall apart here in an instant.

Spending virtually all the season on the Islanders' top defensive pair alongside Noah Dobson, Romanov potted a career-high seven goals while finishing with exactly 22 points for a second straight year. He added 157 hits and 171 blocked shots to go along with a plus-23 rating, by far the best on the team. Early on in his career with Montreal, it appeared as if Romanov might bring a decent amount of offense to the table, but that simply hasn't materialized. As is, he's a grinding, stay-at-home defender who is only a fantasy option in deep leagues which value hits and blocks.

Playing his first full season in Seattle, Tolvanen appeared in 81 of 82 regular-season games, managing 16 goals and a career-high 41 points. Tolvanen added 10 power-play points and a whopping 210 hits for good measure. Tolvanen became a free agent on July 1 but elected to re-sign with the Kraken on a two-year deal worth a shade under $7 million. The 25-year-old Finn is a late-round fantasy option in formats which value hits, but you can almost certainly do better in standard leagues.

Having recently completed his seventh NHL season, Cirelli is fresh off his best offensive year to date. Appearing in 70 games, he set new high-water marks in both goals (20) and points (45), while adding 129 shots on goal, seven power-play points, 64 hits, and 75 blocked shots. Cirelli has developed into one of the better defensive centers in the league, but that isn't going to help anyone from a fantasy perspective. The Lightning let Steven Stamkos walk in free agency, but replaced him with Jake Guenzel, so there's zero reason to believe Cirelli's role will increase from an offensive standpoint. He's only an option in the deepest of fantasy formats.

Ekblad was limited to 51 appearances in 2023-24, registering four goals, 18 points, 98 shots, 59 blocks and 85 hits. After sitting out the first 16 contests of the year following shoulder surgery, he only appeared in nine outings during the final two months of the regular season. Ekblad will need to shoot more often but should rebound from a disappointing 4.1 shooting percentage, especially if he sees an increase in power-play minutes due to Brandon Montour's departure to Seattle via free agency. The 28-year-old Ekblad has 40-point potential in 2024-25.

Eberle was on the trade block much of last year with his contract due to expire at the end of the season, but he elected to stay in Seattle, inking a two-year, $9.5 million extension in March. It seems like a fair payday for a guy coming off a down year. Eberle managed just 17 goals and 44 points in 78 games last season. The stats say he deserved a bit better fate, as Eberle's 10.1 percent shooting percentage was his lowest mark in the past seven years. The upside here is limited, but it wouldn't be a shock to see the 34-year-old threaten the 25-goal mark once again in 2024-25.

Hartman was better last season than two years ago, but still couldn't produce anywhere near the level of his breakout 2021-22 campaign. He finished with 21 goals and 45 points in 74 games. He added 173 shots on goal and a career-high 10 power-play points. Hartman has displayed the ability to move up in the lineup should injuries strike, but he's more of a middle-six, second power-play unit guy if everyone is healthy. Hartman might be worthy of a look on the waiver wire at some point during the season depending on Minnesota's injury situation, but he can be ignored in most formats on draft day.

Zegras was limited to 31 appearances last season, compiling six goals, nine assists and 73 shots. After reaching the 60-point mark in consecutive campaigns before dealing with injury issues in 2023-24, he is a prime bounce-back candidate for 2024-25. Zegras gained confidence down the stretch, collecting two goals and eight points in his final eight outings. He will also benefit from participating in a full training camp after missing most of last year's prep because of a contract dispute. At the very least, he could flirt with the 60-point plateau in the upcoming campaign while occupying a spot in the top six and seeing time on the first power-play combination.

Signed to a massive four-year, $25 million deal by the Ducks prior to last season, Killorn's first year with Anaheim was predictably a disaster. He missed the first ten games of the season with a finger injury and then underwent knee surgery in late January which cost him about a month. All told, Killorn appeared in 63 games, managing 18 goals and 36 points. He was always a strange fit for the rebuilding Ducks, who were trying to work a bunch of young players into their lineup last year and will do so again in 2024-25. Killorn may rebound a bit assuming he can make it through the upcoming season in one piece, but it's difficult to imagine him posting more than 25 goals and 50 points.

The injury bug again bit Jenner hard last season, as the Columbus captain appeared in just 58 regular-season games. He did pot 20-plus goals (22) for a third consecutive year, while tallying 100-plus hits (119) for a second straight campaign. Jenner is a solid player, but he likely shouldn't be a top-six option on a contending team. The Blue Jackets have a ton of young prospects they're trying to work into the mix, not to mention they signed Sean Monahan as an unrestricted free agent. As a result, Jenner is looking at a potential decrease in usage, which would severely damper his already limited fantasy potential.

Provorov's first season in Columbus was rather mediocre. He posted five goals and 32 points in 82 games, numbers right in line with his final couple years in Philadelphia. He shot the puck less than ever (107 shots on goal) and finished with a minus rating (minus-11) for a third straight season. Provorov had some fantasy value earlier in his career when he was running the top power-play unit for the Flyers, but he's nothing more than the second option for the Jackets with Zach Werenski around, meaning there isn't enough production in any single category to make Provorov an option on draft day.

Schmaltz doesn't get talked about much, but he's quietly developed into a steady mid-to-late round offensive fantasy asset the past three seasons. He closed the 2023-24 campaign with 22 goals and 61 points in 79 games, almost exactly in line with his production the prior two seasons. Schmaltz's 21 power-play points were a new career-high, while his 13.9 shooting percentage was his lowest mark during that span, so he may be due some positive regression in the goals scored category. The upside here would appear to be limited, but you can certainly do worse if you are hurting for point production late in your draft.

Maccelli followed up his standout rookie campaign with a strong second season. He posted a career-best 17 goals and 57 points in 82 games, adding 12 points with the man advantage. Maccelli finished the year particularly strong, managing at least one point in eight of Arizona's final 11 games. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 24, Maccelli has settled in as a solid middle-six playmaker. Just keep in mind he rarely shoots the puck (149 shots on goal last season), meaning it will be extremely difficult for him to amass any additional fantasy value barring a change to his style of play, which seems unlikely.

Pulock's season was derailed by a lower-body injury which cost him the better part of two months. He ended up appearing in only 58 regular-season games, posting five goals and 19 points. Pulock is typically good for over 100 of both hits and blocked shots in a full season, but his power-play time has dried up in recent years with the emergence of Noah Dobson. That has all but torpedoed whatever minimal fantasy value the soon-to-be 30-year-old may have had remaining. Pulock is a fade in all formats this coming fall.

Kane's third year in Edmonton was his best to date. He posted 20-plus goals (24) for the eighth time in the past nine seasons, while his 250 hits were by far a new career-best mark. Although he remained healthy much of the regular season, Kane dealt with a sports hernia and a hip injury during the Oilers' run to the Stanley Cup Finals.  Having played through those ailments. he underwent surgery in late September to address multiple concerns and will be sidelined until January at the earliest. Unless you have an IR spot to stash him, Kane figures to be a fade even in dynasty and keeper formats when you consider he's 33 years of age and there is no guarantee he can return to form.

Chiarot again served in a depth role in his second season in Detroit and generated numbers eerily like his first season with the club. He closed with five goals and 20 points in 77 games. Chiarot added 107 shots on goal, 163 hits and 167 blocked shots. The lone significant improvement came in the plus-minus department. Chiarot was just a minus-4, a year removed from posting a woeful minus-31 rating. Now halfway through a four-year contract he signed with the Red Wings in July 2022, Chiarot will reprise a similar role in 2024-25, making him a fantasy option only in deep formats for managers who need help with hits and blocks.

Sherwood improved a bit from a production standpoint in what would be his final season in Nashville. He managed 10 goals and 27 points in 68 games after finishing with no more than seven goals and 13 points in any of his first five NHL seasons. That said, Sherwood knows where his bread is buttered. His makes his living as a grinding, physical winger, as evidenced by the 234 hits he posted a season ago, fourteenth most in the NHL. Sherwood inked a two-year, $3 million contract with the Canucks in free agency, where he will once again work in a bottom-six role and provide deep-league fantasy value in formats which value hits.

Dubois will be joining his fourth organization since entering the league back in 2017-18 after being acquired by the Capitals from the Kings in a swap for goaltender Darcy Kuemper. With his new club, the 2016 third-overall pick should slot into a second-line center role and could see time with the No. 2 power-play as well. After racking up 60-plus points in each of the prior two campaigns, Dubois struggled in LA, registering a disappointing 16 goals and 24 helpers in 82 regular-season contests. If he can rediscover his offensive upside, specifically with the man advantage, Dubois should be capable of getting back to being that 60-point producer.

Stephenson finished with 16 goals a season ago for the second straight year, but his assist totals were way down. As a result, he managed just 51 points after finishing with no fewer than 64 points in either of the prior two years. Clearly not deterred by the dip in production, the Kraken handed Stephenson a seven-year, $43.75 million contract in unrestricted free agency. The monetary commitment suggests Seattle plans on deploying Stephenson as one of their top forwards, but an offensive rebound is far from guaranteed given he's moving to a clearly inferior team. Stephenson is a candidate to be selected way too high on draft day.

Pageau appeared in all 82 regular-season games for the Islanders a season ago, but his offensive numbers dipped once again. He managed just 11 goals and 33 points. The lack of production is directly tied to the fact Pageau is shooting the puck less than ever. He fired just 101 shots on goal a season ago, a stunningly low number for a forward who averaged upwards of 16 minutes (15:55) of ice time per game. The lone bit of good news is that Pageau posted a career-high 196 hits. That said, if you are looking for just hits, you can almost certainly do better and given that his scoring has all but dried up, Pageau isn't a strong option in any fantasy format this coming fall.

Compher arrived in Detroit last season after seven years in Colorado. He managed a career-best 19 goals, finishing with 48 points in 77 games. Compher added double-dight power-play points (10) for a second straight year, while finishing with a minus rating (minus-5) for the first time since the 2018-19 campaign with the Avalanche. Now 29 years of age, Compher is best suited as a third-line center who can move up in the lineup should injuries strike. It's difficult to see him amassing much fantasy value this coming season in anything but the deepest of formats.

After topping the 55-point plateau in three straight seasons, Perron produced 17 goals and 30 assists in 76 contests with Detroit last campaign. He signed a two-year, $8 million contract to join Ottawa in the summer. Perron will likely occupy a middle-six spot in the lineup and see action on the power play in 2024-25. If he plays regularly in the top six, a return to the 50-point plateau is possible, but projecting him for around 45 points with 150-plus shots and 100-plus hits is probably a likelier outcome for the 36-year-old forward.

Returning from a torn labrum which cost him nearly all the 2022-23 campaign, Danforth took on an enhanced role for the going-nowhere Blue Jackets last season. He appeared in 71 games, posting 10 goals and a career-high 26 points. He also topped 100 hits (109) for the first time. Danforth has quietly developed into a valuable third-liner for Columbus, but the usage simply isn't high enough for him to amass any sort of fantasy value moving forward. Look elsewhere on draft day.

Veleno's role increased for the Red Wings in his third full NHL season. Appearing in 80 games, he set new career-best marks in goals (12), assists (16), points (28), shots on goal (86), power-play points (five) and average ice time (13:57). Veleno has durability on his side, having missed just three games over the past two years. That said, Veleno doesn't offer enough production in any one category to be worthy of a draft pick in anything but the deepest leagues this coming season.

From a production standpoint, Schultz's second season in Seattle was like his first. He closed with seven goals and 26 points, including 10 with the man advantage, in 70 games. Never known for his defensive prowess, Schultz also posted a career-worst minus-23 rating, which is saying something considering those terrible Edmonton teams he was on back in the day. Set to play the entirety of this upcoming season at age 34, Schultz remained unsigned as of mid-July. He may need to eventually accept a tryout agreement with a club if he plans on playing in 2024-25, and he figures to see little more than a third-pairing role wherever he lands.
